<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Meets Chinese Vice-Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina told visiting Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo today that
Bangladesh and China are good partners in the fields of economic
development and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Wu at the prime minister's office here, Hasina
said the Bangladeshi people have profound feelings towards China
because the Chinese people have rendered a lot of help to
Bangladesh in its efforts to develop the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed the hope that China would continue
to give more assistance to her country in the fields of
infrastructural development such as energy, transportation and
post and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier expressed satisfaction at the
development of the economic and political relations between the
two countries, adding that the bilateral friendly relations and
close cooperation would continue to develop.
</P>
<P>
He thanked Bangladesh for firmly supporting China on such
issues as human rights, Taiwan and Tibet. China and Bangladesh
will continue to support each other in international affairs and
in developing their own economies, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting with the Bangladeshi prime minister, Chinese
vice-premier paid a courtesy call on Bangladeshi President
Shahabuddin Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
On the issues of human rights, Taiwan and Tibet, Bangladesh is
China's reliable friend, the Bangladeshi president said, adding
that China is Bangladesh's major partner in the development of its
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier today also exchanged views with
Bangladeshi ministers of commerce and industries, and post and
telecommunications on enhancing cooperation in these fields.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, Wu met with Khaleda Zia, chairperson of the
main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party.
</P>
<P>
Wu and his party also visited the Dhaka Export Processing Zone.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier and his party are scheduled to leave
here for Hanoi tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stocks Slide Sharply on Weak Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine stock market fell
today on the third consecutive day due to concerns for poor
corporate earnings and the weakening local currency, with its main
index piercing through the resistance level of 1,950 points.
</P>
<P>
The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index (Phisix) shed
64.92 points or 3.26 percent to close at 1,928.97. The Phisix has
dropped a total of 121.91 points or 5.94 percent this week.
</P>
<P>
The All Shares Index, mirroring the market's general bearish
sentiments, lost 16.82 points at 614.76.
</P>
<P>
All subindices ended in the negative territory, with the
commercial and industrial sector posting the biggest decline of
65.76 points to end at 2,824. The property sector registered the
second biggest drop of 57.58 points to 855.07.
</P>
<P>
Value turnover reached 1.47 billion pesos (U.S. dollars), with
more than 1.3 billion shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Losers beat gainers, 99 to 24, with 36 of the 159 traded issues
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the prevailing bearish sentiment to rising
concerns over poor corporate earnings for the third quarter and
the uncertainty over the Philippine peso.
</P>
<P>
The peso, which had managed to appreciate to less than 34 pesos
to one U.S. dollar last week, has again been weakening against the
U.S. dollar this week.
</P>
<P>
On average, the peso was trading at 34.66 peso to the dollar at
today's local currency market, depreciating 1.27 percent from
Tuesday's average of 34.22 pesos to one dollar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
