<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. Bank Confident About Pakistan Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting World Bank President
James D. Wolfensohn today expressed his confidence in the economic
revival policies of the Pakistani government, saying the bank will
continue to support the country's structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
The economic programs launched by the Pakistan government led
by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif "are quite forward-looking" and the
bank is looking forward to long-term cooperation with it,
Wolfensohn told a news conference here before concluding a
five-day visit to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"There is a strong feeling on our part (about the economic
policies) and now is the moment to give support the government who
appears to be trying to make a difference," Wolfensohn said.
</P>
<P>
He praised the economic measures as "dramatic and necessary
taken by the government to strengthen the banking sector" and
commended trade reforms and fiscal and monetary programs "for
regaining rapid economic growth."
</P>
<P>
This week's approval by the International Monetary Fund of a
soft loan of about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars for Pakistan "is a
vote of confidence in Pakistan's economic management," Wolfensohn
said. "The challenge in future months and years is to sustain this
effort."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is planning to commit upwards of 800 million
U.S. dollars, 10 times more than last year, between now and June
1998, to support Pakistan's National Drainage Program, the second
Social Action Program Projects, and the banking sector reforms, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank president also said he had discussed strategies
to reduce poverty and promote economic development with Prime
Minister Sharif and Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz.
</P>
<P>
At these discussions, Wolfensohn said, they agreed on the
outlines of an approach to future World Bank lending.
</P>
<P>
If the Pakistan government wishes, the bank would help Pakistan
develop long term programs in education, nutrition and rural
infrastructure, particularly rural roads, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> &AMP;0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos today
hinted that the standard bearer of the ruling Lakas-NUCD party in
the 1998 presidential polls will be chosen among the party's seven
presidential aspirants.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly news conference, Ramos said that "outsiders" have
a slim chance to get nominated because the ruling party will
"concentrate on insiders."
</P>
<P>
Among the ruling party, there are seven presidential contenders
trying to get the blessing of the president, who is ineligible to
run for re-election under the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
Of the seven, top runners are Speaker of the House of
Representatives Jose de Venecia, Finance Secretary Roberto de
Ocampo, former defense secretary Renato de Villa and Ramos' sister
Senator Leticia Ramos-Shahani.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Ramos suggested that it is likely for him to anoint an
"outsider" if none of the seven ruling party's presidential
hopefuls is believed to be able to beat opposition candidates.
</P>
<P>
So far, none of the ruling party's presidential aspirants have
fared well in all kinds of opinion polls, which have always been
topped by proclaimed presidential contenders from the opposition
camp.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party earlier extended the deadline for outsiders to
join the group to November 9, when a nationwide consultation of
Lakas leaders and members will start on the nomination of the
presidential bet.
</P>
<P>
The consultation will guide Ramos, chairman of the governing
party, in choosing the party's presidential flag bearer for the
May 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
Ramos is expected to announce his successor before November 27
when the united opposition, the Fight of Patriotic Filipino
Masses, is scheduled to declare their candidate. The president's
endorsement is estimated to be equal to at least 4 million votes.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the ruling party from breaking up, the seven
presidential contenders have been required to sign a covenant
committing their support to whoever is nominated by Ramos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
