<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Oil Revenues to Reach 75 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The six countries of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) are expected to earn more than 75
billion U.S. dollars in oil revenues this year, experts said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The price of crude oil this year stands at 18-19 dollars per
barrel, and the GCC countries with a daily export of about 11.5
million barrels of oil can make more than 75 billion dollars in
the year, said Mohammed Hamdan, a prominent expert of the Abu
Dhabi National Oil Company.
</P>
<P>
This implies that the GCC countries will be hit by a loss of
about 8 billion dollars in this year's oil revenues compared with
that in 1996, when the oil price was at 20 dollars per barrel,
Hamdan said.
</P>
<P>
However, this year's oil price has exceeded the commonly
expected 16.5 dollars per barrel by the GCC nations, leaving them
comfortable room to further cut their budget deficits, according
to an official of the Oil Ministry of the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The six GCC countries, grouping Saudi Arabia, the UAE,
Kuwait, Qatar, Bahrain and Oman, have nearly 45 percent of the
world's proven oil reserves and a daily output of about 13.5
million barrels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Unveils Incentives for Exploring Offshore Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
today unveiled a new incentive package to activate the petroleum
exploration in the country's offshore areas.
</P>
<P>
The package includes a low tax rate of 40 percent compared to
the existing tax capped at 50 percent under the concession system
and accelerated depreciation for capital facilities, a senior
official with the Ministry of Petroleum and Natural Resources said
at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Under the package, the government will not share any rise in
the exploration or development but it will capture the revenues
through profit oil/profit gas on a slicing scale after recovery of
cost which has an upper limit of 85 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The package, which also includes payment or rentals, production
bonus, marine research fee as well as training obligations, would
be applicable for five years and would come into force immediately
after necessary changes are made in the relevant laws, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government hopes that the new package will attract private
investment in the petroleum exploration in the offshore areas,
where no drilling activity has been undertaken for the last seven
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's indigenous supply of oil of around 60,000 barrels
per day meets only about one-sixth of the country's current oil
needs and the balance is met through imports at a high cost of 2.5
billion U.S. dollars, according to official statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
