<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid From Developed Countries to Africa Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Multi-lateral aid from
developed countries to Africa fell 22 percent between 1994 and
1995 and bilateral aid fell 14 percent, according to the latest
British magazine Economist.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the aid of the developed countries to poor countries
between 1994 and 1995 dropped nine percent in real term, a report
in the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
All big donors including Japan, the United States, Germany and
France have confirmed that the slide will continue.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of aid going to the poorest countries fell from
62 percent in 1990 to 51 percent in 1995. A smaller share of a
smaller cake, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The report says while it is true that there is a lot of
private capital going to the developing countries, only five
percent is going to Africa, mainly to mineral extraction which
bring little immediate benefit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank's statistics also shows the
declining trend. In 1996-97 the bank lent 1.74 billion U.S.
Dollars to sub-Saharan Africa, representing a 37 percent fall
from its previous year's loans and credits.
</P>
<P>
The bank's loans for education and health are down 43 percent
and 65 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The report says rich countries are certainly giving less to
the poor countries, and least of all to the poorest.
</P>
<P>
In the sub-Saharan Africa, nearly 40 percent of the population
are poor, according to a U.N. report on human development issued
last June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
