<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Spain Sign Defense Memo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Spain
today signed a memorandum of understanding enabling them to buy
defense equipment from each other, South African Press
Association quoted the Defense Department as saying.
</P>
<P>
The document also provided for exchange of information on
specific defense equipment and related projects between the two
countries, the Defense Department said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Both countries pledged their desire to strengthen defense
industrial relations and to encourage closer cooperation in the
field of defense research and development," the Defense
Department said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed in Pretoria by South African Defense
Secretary Pierre Steyn and Spain's Vice Defense Minister Pedro
Morenes.
</P>
<P>
It also provided for joint trials, tests and evaluations of
such equipment, as well as the exchange of personnel, materials
and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from both countries would meet at least once
every two years to review the progress of cooperation, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Spanish Industry and Energy Minister Joan Pique said Tuesday
that his country would offer South Africa a 10 billion Rand (2.1
billion U.S. Dollars) deal for the supply of corvettes,
submarines and military transport aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The package would include a countertrade offer of 60 projects
for industrial cooperation and joint ventures, Pique said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
Pique is in South Africa to support the Spanish tender for the
sale of weapons to Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Besides Spain, 10 other countries, including Britain, France
and Germany, are also vying for the contract. Tenders will close
at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
South African parliament approved the defense review program
in August, therefore giving the go-ahead for the purchase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Talks on S. Leone Crisis Begin in Conakry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks aimed at putting
an end to the political crisis in Sierra Leone started in
Conakry, Guinea today between the ECOWAS committee of five and a
delegation of the military government of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is
represented by Nigeria, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire, Guinea and Liberia
while the Sierra Leone junta has sent a 21-man delegation to the
meeting which arrived in the Guinean capital today.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS wants to use the talks to compel the junta to step
down and reinstate the legitimate government of President T.
Kabbah who was ousted by the junta in a coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Initial talks broke down in July after junta leader Major
Johnny Paul Koroma declared that he would return democratic rule
to Sierra in four year's time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, military officials in Kenema in eastern Sierra
Leone claimed today that a truck driver, Borbor James was shot
dead and two civilians seriously wounded in an ambush by Nigerian
troops in the ECOWAS at Bandama village on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman said the commercial vehicle with 30 people
on board was passing through the village when it ran into the
ambush and the driver was shot in the head and died instantly.
</P>
<P>
Local journalists said the two seriously wounded victims,
Ibrahim Koroma, a diamond miner and businessman Fuad Bah are now
admitted at Bo Government Hospital and doctors said their
conditions remain serious.
</P>
<P>
West African Peace-keeping troops led by Nigerian soldiers are
in Freetown to implement ECOWAS' sanctions against the military
regime in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tension remains high in Kenema after Tuesday's
bombing by a Nigerian Alfa jet on two targets in Kenema which the
authorities said killed 20 civilians and a military captain.
</P>
<P>
Residents told Xinhua in a telephone interview, that
throughout last night, both Sierra Leone and Nigerian troops
traded heavy artillery fire from their positions. There were no
report of casualties.
</P>
<P>
According to a retired military officer in Kenema, "the
atmosphere is so tense that renewed fighting can break out at any
time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
