<HEADLINE> Trade Unions Participate in International Activities  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 3,000 people have attended the activities and
discussed wide-ranging issued related to economic development, the
living standards, workers' rights and interests, the creation of
more employment opportunities, applications of new technology, and
foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The CFTU has listed increasing exchanges with the International
Labor Organization (ILO) and participating in multilateral
activities as priority tasks.
</P>
<P>
China resumed its participation in ILO activities in 1983, and
the country has since placed great stress on participating in
related activities, including the annual International Labor
Conference and activities sponsored by the ILO's special
committees and industrial committee.
</P>
<P>
The CFTU also participated in the International Conference on
Population and Development in Cairo, the World Summit for Social
Development in Copenhagen, and Beijing's World Conference on Women.
</P>
<P>
CFTU representative attending the World Conference on Women met
with delegations from more than 120 foreign trade unions. The
forum on Labor Safety for Women attached representatives from more
than 100 countries, and attracted worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
The official in charge of the CFTU International Dept.
underlined that China's trade union organizations pay great
attention to developing friendly relations with counterparts in
African countries and other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China's trade unions hope to expand exchanges and
cooperation with trade unions in other countries, as well as
international and regional labor organizations, he said. They also
hope to engage in joint effort to safeguard basic rights and
interests of workers worldwide and promote the sound development
of international labor movement.  
</P>
