<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Tight-lipped on Participation of Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will remain tight-lipped
on its participation in the November Middle East and North Africa
Economic Conference (MENA) until three to four days before its
opening, President Hosni Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
"I will not disclose Egypt's final decision because if we
announce that we will not take part, Egypt will be accused of
making its decision too early and prodding others not to attend,"
today's London-based Arabic daily Al-Hayat quoted Mubarak as
saying in an interview.
</P>
<P>
"We will remain silent while watching the developments of the
Middle East peace process until the last moment," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Who knows we might witness a miracle," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has hinged its participation in the controversial
conference, which is to be held in Doha, Qatar, on November 16-18,
on progress in the problematic Palestinian-Israeli peace track.
</P>
<P>
A number of countries like Syria, Lebanon, Saudi Arabia and the
United Arab Emirates as well as the Palestinian National Authority
have threatened to boycott the Israeli-attending conference in
protest against Israel's hardline policy towards the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On many occasions, however, Cairo has voiced pessimism over the
prospects for any breakthrough in the ongoing U.S.-brokered
committee talks in the region -- the first Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations after seven months of deadlock -- and higher level
talks in Washington at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
"What is the use of holding such a conference if every party is
turning its back against the other," Mubarak questioned.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu disrespects the
signed agreements. How can we trust a man who does not honor his
word?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Washington should capitalize on its relationship with Israel to
give impetus to the peace process, Mubarak told Al-Hayat.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent bid to create a suitable atmosphere to convene
the MENA conference in time, the U.S. has sent its Mideast peace
envoy Dennis Ross to the region to speed up the work of the nine
committees haggling about outstanding issues from a 1995 interim
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president said that he fully agrees with King
Hussein of Jordan, who said recently that he has lost confidence
in Netanyahu but that the Israelis have to be won over to promote
peace.
</P>
<P>
"We have to deal with the Israeli people if it is peace we
see," he said, adding that peace is for both the Arabs and
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Jordan announced its decision Monday to go to the conference
for regional economic cooperation that was initiated in 1994 as a
direct spinoff of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has invited 92 countries and organizations and expects
some 2,500 foreign participants to the annual gathering, the
fourth after the previous ones held in Casablanca, Amman and
Cairo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Calls for Special Programs for Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today urged other
ASEAN member countries to identify clear and specific programs for
rural development and poverty eradication in the region.
</P>
<P>
The rural development and poverty eradication committee under
the ASEAN Secretariat will have its functions streamlined so that
it has clear and specific programs to implement, Malaysian Rural
Development Minister Annuar Musa said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Rural development in ASEAN must be given the new push. We must
identify the right programs to facilitate such environments which
are conducive to faster development," he told reporters after
meeting officials from Brunei and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The officials are here to attend the inaugural meeting of ASEAN
Ministers on Rural Development and Eradication of Poverty which
begins tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to produce an agreement on forming a
permanent forum within the framework of ASEAN to discuss matters
on rural development and poverty eradication and a related action
plan, according to Malaysian officials of the rural development
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The minister said there was a common stand that the region must
be more aggressive in rural development and poverty eradication.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia and other member countries hoped for greater
cooperation at the officials' level and for exchange of ideas and
information among experts on rural development and poverty
eradication issues.
</P>
<P>
Meetings at the senior officials' level are progressing well,
he said, adding that it has been agreed that a meeting among rural
development experts would be held in December in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
However, he said no deadline should be imposed for poverty
eradication in the region as member countries should be allowed to
set a timeframe well-suited to their own countries' development.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
