<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Sets Higher Inflation Target for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
raised its inflation rate target for 1998 to 6.5 to 7 percent from
the original estimate of 5 to 5.5 percent, local television
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the National Economic and Development Authority
(NEDA), the country's planning agency, were quoted as explaining
that the adjustment was made due to several factors, including the
El Nino weather phenomenon and the current currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
An increase in the price of basic food items, which account for
58 percent of the consumer price index (CPI), is expected to be
brought about by a projected serious drought accompanying El Nino,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the El Nino phenomenon which is now being felt in
the country in the third quarter of this year is expected to
result in a shortage in the supply of food items, particularly
rice and corn, starting next year.
</P>
<P>
To avert the scarcity in the supply of rice, the government has
drawn up plans to import some 300,000 to 400,000 tons of rice by
the first half this year.
</P>
<P>
Wage adjustments and higher production cost, both a result of
the weakening peso, will likewise exert great pressure on prices.
Another inflationary factor is the country's presidential and
parliamentary elections scheduled for May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso, a victim of the current Southeast Asian
currency turmoil, has tumbled more than 31 percent against the
U.S. dollar since its effective devaluation by the central bank in
July.
</P>
<P>
The peso was trading at an average rate of 34.66 pesos against
the dollar at today's Philippine Dealing System, the country's
official currency exchange.
</P>
<P>
Due to the sliding peso and skyrocketing interest rates, the
government earlier scaled down its gross national product (GNP)
target for 1998 to 6.5 to 7.5 percent from the original projection
of 7.5 to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic product (GDP) estimate for next year was
also revised down to 6 to 7 percent from the previous expectation
of 6.5 to 7.5 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
