<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Leaders to Craft "2020 Vision" in December </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) member countries will forge a new
"ASEAN 2020 vision" when they meet in December this year, the
Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon was quoted
as saying that the updated ASEAN 2020 vision will guide the
regional grouping in the first decades of the next century.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to that vision as the new embodiment of the
Southeast Asian community spirit for the new age," Siazon told
members of the ASEAN Standing Committee (ASC) who are attending
the on-going ASC meeting here.
</P>
<P>
ASC is the central coordinating organ of ASEAN. As the current
ASEAN chair, Siazon also chairs ASC whose members include the
director generals of all ASEAN national secretariats.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Undersecretary Rodolfo Severino is slated to
take over at the end of the year from Dato Ajit Singh of Malaysia
as new ASEAN Secretary General, a ministerial position he will
hold for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said ASEAN leaders expect ASEAN 2020 "to enunciate our
hope for a new Southeast Asian community whose political,
economic, cultural and moral influences are a positive and
constructive presence in the global scene in the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, he added, hopes to see ASEAN grow into a
concert of Southeast Asian nations at peace within themselves,
with one another, and with the world; an economic commonwealth of
states that act together to secure prosperity for themselves at
the expense of no one.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN, he said, has become what it is today, "model of regional
cooperation and consensus in the promotion of peace, stability and
prosperity" through three principles -- national and regional
resilience, unity in diversity and open regionalism.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
