<HEADLINE> Somalia's Al-Itihad Proposes Peace Talk With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Fundamentalist
group of Al-Itihad today proposed to hold peace talks with
Ethiopia in a bid to settle the crisis in Somalia's southwestern
border region of Gedo.
</P>
<P>
In a communique, the most hard-line Islamist organization in
Somalia has offered a peaceful settlement between it and the
allied forces of Ethiopia along with the armed group from the
Marehan Somali National Front faction (SNF) led by former defense
minister General Omar Hagi Masalle.
</P>
<P>
The statement was signed by five top Al-Itihad men including
Chairman Sheikh Mohamed Hagi Yussuf and it proposed that the
conflict be solved through a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"Al-Itihad is ready to meet, talk and negotiate with anyone
representing our rival sides," said the three-page statement.
</P>
<P>
However, Al-Itihad has condemned Ethiopia's alleged continuing
military occupation of parts of Somalia and called on the
Ethiopian government to pull its troops out of Bulo Hawo, Dolow
and Luq towns of Gedo region.
</P>
<P>
The organization has not set any time or venue for the
proposed talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Al-Itihad said they will morally and materially support a
lasting solution to ending the hostility in the region, but added
that a total withdrawal of Ethiopian forces could be a major step
toward a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
This peace appeal was unexpected in consideration of the stiff
and extreme position of Al-Itihad regarding the conflict in Gedo
region.
</P>
<P>
The region has been quiet since the forces of Al-Itihad were
forcefully driven out of the area in June this year.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has denied any military presence in the region, but
independent sources and international aid workers and the
chairman of SNF himself have clarified the involvement of
Ethiopian forces in Gedo region.
</P>
<P>
In an early interview, Chairman of SNF Masalle admitted that
he had invited the Ethiopian forces to help him in eradicating
the Moslem fundamentalist group of Al-Itihad which had controlled
the area.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia itself has accused Al-Itihad of carrying out
terrorist activities inside Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Males Zenawi, the Ethiopian Prime Minister warned that his
forces will strike wherever the Al-Itihad forces might go to.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the only faction that Al-Itihad had got some
sympathy from became the faction led by Hussein Mohamed Aidid who
in turn accused Ethiopia of backing his political rivals.
</P>
<P>
The National Salvation Council formed in Sodare of Ethiopia
has firmly stood against Al-Itihad and Hussein Aidid's position
toward Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Instead it called on them to attend what they called the
upcoming national reconciliation conference anticipated to take
place in the northwestern town of Bossaso in early November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
