<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Kilo of Cocaine Seized in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South African narcotics
bureau detectives today netted four kilogram of cocaine with an
estimated street value of 1.2 million Rand (255,000 U.S. Dollars)
at an airport here, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
A member of the bureau, Jaco Koen, said it was the largest
amount of cocaine captured in more than three months.
</P>
<P>
The cocaine was found in four tins of baby food in the baggage
of a woman passenger who had arrived from Sao Paulo, Brazil at
around noon at Johannesburg International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Police acted on a profile drawn up about a possible smuggler
and pounced after the woman went through customs, Koen said.
</P>
<P>
Cocaine coming into the country was usually about 90 percent
pure before it would be cut with other chemicals and distributed,
Koen said.
</P>
<P>
The drug could be multiplied by seven times before
distribution, which means that today's haul could have been sold
for 8.4 million Rand (1.8 million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The largest amount of cocaine seized so far by police at the
airport came last year, when police netted 21 kilograms with an
estimated value of 6.3 million Rand (1.3 million Dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
