<HEADLINE> Mandela Arrives in Libya for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela arrived in Tripoli today for a visit to Libya during which
he will hold talks with Libyan Leader Muammar Gaddafi mainly on
bilateral political and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Libya is the second leg of Mandela's north Africa tour, which
has taken him to Egypt and will also cover Tunisia and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's tour is aimed at promoting trade and military
cooperation and the exchange of views on other humanitarian
issues, including the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's visit to Libya has aroused criticism from the United
States, but the South African leader considered it beyond
anyone's right to define which countries to visit or not to visit.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo, who was accompanying
Mandela during his visit to Egypt, called Tuesday in Cairo for the
immediate lifting of U.N. sanctions imposed on Libya.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed an air ban on Libya in 1992
to force the surrender of two Libyans wanted in the 1988 bombing
of Pan AM Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270
people. 
</P>
