<HEADLINE> Nigeria Urged Not to Send Delegation to Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON October 22 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
Commonwealth Emeka Anyaok has urged Nigeria, whose Commonwealth
membership has been suspended, not to send a delegation to the
Edinburgh Commonwealth Summit to be held later this week.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth chief made the appeal a day after the Nigerian
government demanded a hearing when Commonwealth leaders discuss
Nigeria's suspended membership.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth spokesman Michael Fathers was quoted by the
Reuters as saying today, "He (Anyaok) sent a letter today to
Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi strongly urging that no
Nigerian delegation should travel to Edinburgh."
</P>
<P>
"The letter points out that as Nigeria is suspended it cannot
participate in Commonwealth meetings. Nigeria's attendance would
require the agreement of all participants of the meeting," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian foreign minister said in a letter to Anyaoku that
"Nigeria should not be tried in absentia. We have therefore
concluded arrangements in Nigeria for our delegation to fly direct
from Abuja straight to Edinburgh" when the Commonwealth discusses
the Nigeria issue. 
</P>
