<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Oil Companies Fare Well in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Oil Companies in the United
States reported profits increases this summer because of a roughly
3.5 percent growth in demand compared with the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Big companies like Exxon, Texaco and Amoco saw robust
third-quarter earnings as reflected in their reports released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Their net income rose 16.7 percent, 12.9 percent and 18 percent
respectively over the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
Most of other major oil companies are also expected to show
higher earnings for the quarter, having run their refineries at
full capacity to meet the surge in demand for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the business boom to the decline in crude
oil prices, heavy vacation driving and growing tendency of
customers to buy sport vehicles consuming more gas instead of
conventional cars.
</P>
<P>
However, they warn that it may be difficult for the rest of the
year to see such a surge to sustain as a recent rise in crude oil
prices has a negative impact on refining profit in the first weeks
of the new quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Stresses Need for Political Process in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. diplomat
underlined here today the need to concentrate on the political
process for a settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth Brill was commenting on the
statements made by U.S. Presidential Emissary for Cyprus Richard
Holbrooke, who criticized Tuesday the U.S. State Department for
not accepting that Turkish aircraft harassed the plane of the
Greek defense minister last week.
</P>
<P>
Brill told reporters that Holbrooke expressed his views very
clearly, but "I think that we all want to move on from this and
start engaging in constructive activity."
</P>
<P>
The U.S., he said, wants to promote a negotiating process and
get people to focus on the core political issues and not on
military activities.
</P>
<P>
"It is time for very serious work and time to take advantage
of some of the opportunities that are out there, particularly
next year," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke is determined on finding a way to move the Cyprus
issue forward for a settlement in a constructive political sense,
Brill noted.
</P>
<P>
He also said the U.S. considered there was a moratorium of
flights over Cyprus, which ended with the overflights during the
annual military exercise Cyprus conducted on October 10-14, with
the participation of the Greek armed forces.
</P>
<P>
But Cyprus Foreign Ministry issued a statement Tuesday,
clarifying that "there has never been an agreement for a
moratorium of overflights in Cyprus' sovereign airspace."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, have long been at odds
over this eastern Mediterranean island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
