<HEADLINE> Bus Bombing Averted in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkish police succeeded in
averting a bus bombing attack in southeastern Turkey today, the
Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
A militant of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) was
captured when he tried to implant a bomb in a police vehicle in
Elazig city, some 540 kilometers southeast of Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The bomb is very powerful, Elazig Governor Luffullah Bilgin was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The PKK member, a post worker, admitted that he has provided
clothes, communication equipments and other necessities to the PKK
rebels in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK, which is reportedly trying to build new bases in
the Black Sea region, carried out a series of actions over
the past weeks, including abduction of civilians, sudden attacks
on military posts and police vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Governors, police chiefs and gendarmerie commanders of 10
Black Sea cities will meet Saturday in Giresun town to discuss
effective ways of combating the PKK activities in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting the Turkish government since 1984
for the establishment of an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
