<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Liberalize Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official here
today urged members of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) to pursue liberalization of insurance industry
cautiously to avoid proliferation of under-capitalized insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made by Deputy Finance Minister Godfrey
Simasiku while opening the one-day 11th meeting of the Council of
Bureaux on regional third party motor vehicle insurance scheme.
</P>
<P>
Simasiku told participants that governments must ensure that
sound insurance legislation and supervision are in place and that
regulatory and supervisory authorities are equipped with
technical capacity to ensure that emerging insurance companies
have adequate capital and that they are solvent.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Simasiku also urged insurance companies in the
region to engage in cross-border investments as a means of
increasing their service capacity.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, which originated from a preferential trade area for
the region in 1993 and now groups 20 countries, aims to achieve a
full free trade area by 2000, a customs union with a zero tariff
on products produced within the common market and freedom of
movement of people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
