<HEADLINE> Iran Blames Germany for Failure of EU Envoys' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has blamed Germany for the failure of the return to
Tehran of the European Union members' ambassadors, Iran's official
news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Kharrazi as saying that Germany is responsible for
the existing problems and for failure of the efforts to solve the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Iran has done its utmost and has no new proposals in this
regard at the moment, Kharrazi said in response to a recent
statement by German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said Germany will not accept discriminatory conditions
and that talks will be held with Iran only when disputes are
resolved.
</P>
<P>
Iran insists that EU members' ambassadors can return to Tehran,
but the German envoy must be the last to be back.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi was quoted as saying that "Kinkel has lost valuable
opportunities and I do not think that time would work in Germany's
favor."
</P>
<P>
Iran is an independent country, whose foreign policies are made
in accordance with its national interest, he added.
</P>
<P>
EU's 15 members, except Greece, called back their ambassadors
in Tehran after a German court ruled last April that Iranian
leaders ordered the 1992 killing of four Kurdish dissidents in
Berlin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
