<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Oil Companies Fare Well in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Oil Companies in the United
States reported profits increases this summer because of a roughly
3.5 percent growth in demand compared with the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Big companies like Exxon, Texaco and Amoco saw robust
third-quarter earnings as reflected in their reports released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Their net income rose 16.7 percent, 12.9 percent and 18 percent
respectively over the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
Most of other major oil companies are also expected to show
higher earnings for the quarter, having run their refineries at
full capacity to meet the surge in demand for gasoline.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the business boom to the decline in crude
oil prices, heavy vacation driving and growing tendency of
customers to buy sport vehicles consuming more gas instead of
conventional cars.
</P>
<P>
However, they warn that it may be difficult for the rest of the
year to see such a surge to sustain as a recent rise in crude oil
prices has a negative impact on refining profit in the first weeks
of the new quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
