<HEADLINE> Greece Satisfied With Holbrooke's Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas today expressed satisfaction over the statements
made by U.S. special presidential emissary for Cyprus Richard
Holbrooke on the Turkish harassment of Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos' plane last week.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said Tuesday that the harassment of a plane carrying
Tsohatzopoulos to and from Cyprus last week was a fact, blaming
the U.S. State Department for not recognizing it outright.
</P>
<P>
Greece had kept the positive positions expressed and recorded
the negative ones, Reppas said. "What now remains to be seen is
how Washington will proceed concerning issues which are in
progress and whether Mr. Holbrooke's observations will have
practical consequences," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tsohatzopoulos today welcomed Holbrooke's
statements, saying that Holbrooke was near to the reality and
"this confirms his credibility as a mediator."
</P>
<P>
Greece strongly condemned the statements by U.S. State
Department spokesman James Rubin as "unprecedented and
unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Late Monday, Rubin said that Tsohatzopoulos' flight to Cyprus
for military exercises was "an overflight that violated an agreed
up moratorium." 
</P>
</TEXT>
