<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yabloko May Drop No-Confidence to Government:  Faction Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Yabloko faction
would drop its no-confidence motion against the government if it
went through the problem of the taxation code to the end, leader
of the Yabloko parliamentary faction Grigory Yavlinsky said today.
</P>
<P>
Yavlinsky told reporters that the document which his faction
considered to be "senseless and harmful" should be recalled.
</P>
<P>
He meanwhile voiced the strong doubt that Sergei Baburin
representing the People's Power bloc in parliament would collect
the necessary number of signatures to initiate a no-confidence
motion against the government.
</P>
<P>
The Yabloko leader noted that once the head of the government
had recalled the taxation code from the Duma, "the issue of no
confidence would have died without any concessions to communists."
</P>
<P>
If the premier of the government did not withdraw the tax code,
he added, the code's handling under the Duma's procedure would
only result in "protracting this issue."
</P>
<P>
Another report said that Igor Shabdurasulov, a government
senior spokesman, today criticized the manner of Yavlinsky as
"unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
He told Itar-Tass in an interview that only an investigator had
the right to demand only a concrete `yes' or `no' answer to a
question, and not the leader of the Duma faction who was trying to
teach the chairman of the government how to fulfill orders of the
president.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin Tuesday sent a message to Duma
faction leaders, which contained an instruction to the government
to withdraw a draft tax code from the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Communist faction, the largest in the lower house
of parliament, today withdrew its motion of no-confidence in the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
