<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Conference to Stress Child Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton are hoping a White House
conference will raise awareness of the need for higher quality
child care.
</P>
<P>
In previewing the first-ever White House Conference on Child
Care to be held Thursday, Mrs. Clinton said today the meeting
would examine the full range of available options.
</P>
<P>
While promising the president would announce some policy moves,
including the possibility of federal subsidies in the future, she
said that much of the job, including licensing and training, falls
to the states and private industry.
</P>
<P>
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala said it
wasn't really a question of needing a lot more cash and often
small amounts of training or harsher licensing requirements showed
marked improvements.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry said Clinton was "very
keen on stimulating a national discussion," and that the first
couple hoped the meeting "will call national attention to an issue
policymakers historically have ignored."
</P>
<P>
About 75 percent of American families with young children use
some form of child care and most are not pleased with it,
according to a Parents Magazine poll released today.
</P>
<P>
The random poll of some 2,000 parents generated 450 responses
that were projected nationally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
