<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Begins Talks With S. Leone Junta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Talks between Sierra Leone's
military junta and the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) on resolving the crisis in the country started this
evening in Conakry, capital of Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting are the delegation of soldiers and
civilians sent by the junta, foreign ministers from Nigeria,
Ghana, Guinea, Cote d'ivoire and Liberia, as well as
representatives from the Organization of African Unity and the
United Nations, according to the British Broadcasting
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the two sides over the restoration of
Sierra Leone's legitimate government led by president Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah broke down in July this year when the junta announced to
stay in power until 2001.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the talks followed a UN sanctions against
the junta announced a fortnight ago.
</P>
<P>
Before that, the junta was reported to have expressed
willingness to resume talks for several times.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional organization ECOWAS answered the call ten
days ago on conditions that the junta must negotiate in good
faith and the talks should strictly be within the mandate of
ECOWAS and the UN Security Council, which focuses on the junta's
immediate quit and return of power to the ousted government of
Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The progress at the on-going negotiation is not yet available
at the movement but it is widely expected that the resumption of
the talks will help break the political impasse over the crisis
in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0060 </DOCNO>
