<HEADLINE> Mozambique Urged to Reduce Delivery Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Carlos Tiny, residential
representative of the World Health Organization (WHO) in
Mozambique, today called on the Mozambican health authorities to
work out a concrete plan to reduce the death rate during
delivery.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal at a seminar held here today which is
focusing its discussions on how to implement the national
integration program of mother-infant health, and other programs
such as birth control and expanded vaccination.
</P>
<P>
The WHO official expressed his concern that Mozambique, whose
delivery death rate is between 38 and 40 percent, has no program
to reduce such death cases.
</P>
<P>
He said that the WHO will continue to support the Mozambican
government to revert such a situation.
</P>
<P>
The seminar attended by about 60 people opened on Tuesday and
will close at the end of this month. 
</P>
