<HEADLINE> Unity Government in Brazzaville Possible: SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Kaire Mbuende, the
executive secretary of the South African Development Community
(SADC) said today it is still possible that a government of
national unity might be formed in the Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Last week, forces of Congo's rebel leader Dennis Sassou
Nguesso, backed by Angolan troops, took control of the country's
capital Brazzaville and overthrew the government of President
Pascal Lissouba.
</P>
<P>
"It is a deplorable situation that we had a change of
government in this way," Mbuende told a press briefing, quoted by
South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
"I like to believe that the time has come for Africa to change
its governments only through elections."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, there is still hope for a government of
national unity in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are informed that all is not lost. there are ongoing
negotiations... there is the possibility of creating a government
of national unity and paving the way for elections." 
</P>
