<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Violation of Cypriot Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today rebuffed the
Cypriot accusation that Turkish military jets violated the
airspace of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press briefing here, Turkish Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Omer Akbel said that Turkish aircraft have been flying
over the area without breaking any international rules.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, it is the Greek side that violated an
agreement banning flights of warplanes in military exercises, "
Akbel said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's remarks followed the Cypriot government's
Tuesday protest against the alleged Turkish military jets'
violation of Cypriot airspace
</P>
<P>
In a letter addressed to the United Nations Security Council,
Cyprus said that Turkey's provocative military flights "cause
serious concern and heighten tensions in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The Greek-Turkish relations have been worsening since the
Cypriot government affirmed that it would not give up the plan to
deploy S-300 missiles purchased from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus held a military exercise codenamed "Victory '97" from
October 10 to 14, with the participation of Greek air and
naval forces.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, Turkish forces and Turkish Cypriot militia have
announced that they will stage joint war games early next month.
</P>
<P>
Greek and Turkish military jets had met in the air but nothing
serious took place.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish troops
 landed and took over the northern third of it in the wake of an
aborted coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community efforts to solve the
problem have failed due to the differences between the rival
Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Decline on Wall Street, Hong Kong Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all fell heavily Wednesday, undermined by UK's uncertain position
on the European single currency, profit- taking on Wall Street and
continued big fall in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index on the London market suffered the steepest
decline in two months and ended 77.1 points lower at 5,148.8 amid
a sharp downturn in index futures.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that weakness on Wall Street, heavy selling in
Singapore and further jitters in Hong Kong also weighed on market
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The index was dragged down by a sharp fall of shares of Hong
Kong-linked firms such as HSBC Holdings, Cable &AMP; wireless and
Standard Chartered.
</P>
<P>
Subdued retail sales figures in September failed to cheer the
market as the figures were clouded by several factors, including
the impact of shops closing for the funeral of Diana, Princess of
Wales.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt failed to sustain its early gains
and ended well below their best levels as traders reported
disappointment at low volumes and a weaker dollar.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index closed up 31.95 points at 4,171.45. However,
in later screen-based trade the IBIS DAX index ended at 4,124.86,
47.61 points lower.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris dropped back below the 3,000 level to
end 31.83 points down at 2,958.06. Concerns about the near-term
outlook for European interest rates and weak bonds weighed on the
market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls on to Respect Varieties of Cultures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- As the world was
developing towards globalization and integration, the varieties of
cultures should be respected, Chinese delegate Cui Ying said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the fifty-second session of the General Assembly,
Cui said culture had been playing a more and more important role
in the international relations and the international society had
attached greater importance to the relationship between culture
and development.
</P>
<P>
Cui said the world was so colorful because all countries and
nationalities had their own cultures. Exchanges of cultures
between different countries had reached an unprecedented level in
depth and width.
</P>
<P>
Cui said culture and development were interdependent. Culture
reflected a country's fundamental characteristics of economy and
politics and it helped to promote the development of economy and
politics.
</P>
<P>
Cui said UNESCO would hold its 29th session soon. China hoped
that the session would recommend measures for the further
development of culture in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary Meets Hong Kong Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook Wednesday met with Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of China's
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
He praised Tung for developments in Hong Kong since it was
returned to China on July 1 at the end of 156 years of British
colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
"We are very pleased with the way in which the Hong Kong
economy and Hong Kong society has developed since the handover,"
Cook told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased that the concept of 'one country, two systems'
is actually working in practice," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cook said that he was expecting to visit Beijing and Hong Kong
earlier next year so as to further enhance bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, who arrived here Tuesday for a three-day visit,
briefed the British foreign secretary on the latest development in
Hong Kong. They also exchanged views on economic and trade
cooperation between Hong Kong and Britain and on the remaining
aspects of Vietnamese boat people problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
