<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US House Passes Stopgap Bill For Government Running </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives voted overwhelmingly for a stopgap bill today to
keep government running.
</P>
<P>
The House approved the legislation by voice vote to keep the
government functioning through November 7 when lawmakers hope to
adjourn for the year.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said the U.S. Senate probably
would vote on the measure Thursday when an earlier stopgap bill
expires.
</P>
<P>
The bill is needed because only five of the 13 spending bills
for fiscal 1998 that began October 1 have been enacted.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Congressional leaders hope the extension will give
lawmakers enough time to strike compromises among themselves and
with Clinton on lingering budgetary issues.
</P>
<P>
House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bob Livingston said
today that he hopes the congress can get onto completing its work
on the budget by November 7.
</P>
<P>
On the last days of fiscal 1997 which ended on September 30,
the U.S. Congress passed a stopgap spending bill to let federal
agencies function through October 23 and President Clinton signed
the measure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barshefsky Announces China Insurance License to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Charlene Barshefsky, the
U.S. Trade Representative, today announced that China has approved
the application for Aetna to operate a joint venture insurance
operation in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the Office of U.S. Trade Representative said
confirmation of the action on Aetna's application came at a
meeting in New York City by the China Economic and Trade
Delegation, a group of high level officials visiting this country
to seek commercial contracts with U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, many U.S. firms have already established
representative offices in China, but they have not been permitted
to open business operations there. Aetna, the third largest
insurance company for life and health in the United States in
1996, becomes the second U.S. insurer to operate in China.
</P>
<P>
"Aetna is one of a number of U.S. insurance companies which
have been seeking a license to enter the large China market for
years," noted Barshefsky. "While we certainly welcome this news,
an economy as large and competitive as China's must undertake
further substantial market-opening actions, including in the
insurance and financial services sectors." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0077 </DOCNO>
