<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Turkey against Building Tension with Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States was
concerned on Wednesday that Turkish fighter jets had buzzed the
plane of the Greek defense minister on his way back from military
exercises over Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"We have made clear to our Turkish allies the seriousness with
which we view the information we have received and the need to
ensure that any future Turkish activities do not contribute to an
atmosphere of tension between Turkey and its neighbors," State
Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
It is important that Turkey and Greece both ensure that a
Turkish military exercise scheduled for early November does not
trigger a new confrontation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also repeated a U.S. call on the two NATO allies to
continue their promise of banning flights of combat aircraft over
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Greek defense ministry said earlier that two pairs of
Turkish F-16s buzzed the plane carrying Defense Minister Akis
Tsochadzopoulos from Cyprus, as it flew about 80 miles southeast
of the Aegean island of Rhodes. The Turkish planes were
intercepted by eight Greek fighter jets, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
