<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: SAR Government Determined to Defend HK Dollar  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) has said it is determined
to maintain the stable status of the Hong Kong dollar, despite the
continuing fall of the local share market in the past four days.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong's stock market plunged today for the fourth day
this week, shedding 1,211 points to close at 10,426. On Wednesday,
the Hang Seng Index, the key indicator of the Hong Kong stock
market, closed at 11,637, down 765 points, the lowest finish since
April this year.
</P>
<P>
Meeting reporters in London today, Chief Executive of the SAR
Tung Chee Hwa said his government was "tremendously" determined to
defend the stable status of the Hong Kong dollar and maintain its
peg to the U.S. dollar, or the linked exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"We have every confidence this can be done and will be done.
The fundamentals in Hong Kong are very good," Tung said. "We have
very conservative management of our fiscal policy, we are running
a huge budget surplus, we have a fiscal reserve of over 50 billion
U.S. dollars, foreign exchange reserves over 85 billion U.S.
dollars, one of the largest anywhere in the world."
</P>
<P>
He emphasized: "We are determined to maintain the exchange rate
mechanism and to do this we have signalled to the market our
determination, the interest rate has gone up and as a result of
that there is a short-term repercussion on the stock market, and
this is to be expected."
</P>
<P>
Before attending a meeting of the Provisional Legislative
Council here today, Administrative Secretary Anson Chan told
reporters: "I advise everybody to stay calm." "I would only stress
that the market is operating normally," she said.
</P>
<P>
"You want to buy, you want to sell and that's the way it should
be," Chan pointed out. "Of course, Hong Kong cannot escape being
affected in the short-term by what's happening in the region. But
the important thing is that our economic fundamentals remain very
strong and we have absolute determination to defend the Hong Kong
dollar."
</P>
<P>
Reiterating the determination of the SAR government to defend
the Hong Kong dollar, Financial Secretary of the SAR government
Donald Tsang today described it as the top priority now to defend
the linked exchange rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Draws up Action Plan for Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The seven member countries of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) have
drawn up an action plan for the transition to a South Asian Free
Trade Area (SAFTA) by 2001, the Kathmandu-based SAARC Secretariat
said today.
</P>
<P>
The action plan will serve as a blueprint for successive rounds
of trade negotiations by the SAARC's Inter-Governmental Group on
Trade Liberalization, the secretariat said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting of the SAARC's Inter-Governmental Expert
Group (IGEG) on Transition to SAFTA also finalized the terms of
reference of an in-depth Regional Study on the implications to the
member states of progression from the South Asian Preferential
Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) to SAFTA, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The Regional Study will identify all non-tariff barriers in
this process, discriminatory practices and implications of revenue
losses and trade imbalances among the SAARC member countries, said
the press release.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 representatives from the SAARC member countries --
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka -- attended the three-day meeting which concluded today at
the SAARC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The IGEG will meet again in January 1998, the press release
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: SAR Government Determined to Defend HK Dollar  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Together with several other senior SAR financial officials, he
told a news conference that the stock market could return to
normal only after the stabilization of the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
In general, Hong Kong's economy remains stable, he said.
</P>
<P>
Today's stock market drop followed three days of steep falls,
with investors gripped by panic selling on fears of higher
interest rates and currency instability.
</P>
<P>
The market has been further weakened mainly by selling
pressures from overseas and domestic funds managers and by renewed
currency volatility in the Asia-Pacific region, analysts here
said.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports that the main reason for today's fall
appeared to be a huge rise in short-term interbank rates here.
Banks here announced earlier today that their prime rate would
rise by 0.75 of a percentage point to 9.5 percent from Friday.
</P>
<P>
The hike appeared designed to head off borrowing for
speculative attacks on the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) triggered
panic selling earlier today when it stopped normal rate finance
for banks which it suspected were using the money for attacks on
the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
Speculators have been blamed for slumps in the value of several
Southeast Asian currencies following the float of the Thai baht in
July, but Hong Kong had largely been spared the turbulence until
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said the SAR government was hoping to starve
speculators of funds to ease pressure on the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar is the only Asian currency still pegged to
the U.S. dollar. Several other Asian currencies have plunged since
July in a wave of turmoil sweeping markets from Indonesia and
Malaysia to Singapore and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Questioned by reporters about the tumbling stock market, Tsang
said today: "I am not worried at all, because it is a market. A
market, of course, depends on the sentiments," he said. "I don't
think it is a matter for people to panic about, but I believe very
strongly in defending our dollar."
</P>
<P>
He is of the view that Hong Kong's companies are still making
good profits and they are turning in good dividends for the
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
Tung, who is in London for a visit, added that he believed the
stock market was sound and would eventually correct itself.
</P>
<P>
"All our major companies have very good performance, the growth
in profits is all double-digit, and the fundamentals again are
very good, basically because the Hong Kong economy is good," he
said. "And there is some short-term impact on the stock but we are
quite sure the market will find the right level and we are very
confident of our future."
</P>
<P>
As another step in fighting the speculators, the HKMA announced
tonight that the official foreign exchange reserves of the SAR,
including those held in the Land Fund, stood at 88.1 billion U.S.
dollars at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is now the world's third largest holder of foreign
reserves after Japan and the interior areas of China, the HKMA
noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
