<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Holds Conference on Child Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today he intends to work out a plan by January that would
improve day care for children with the help of businesses and
schools.
</P>
<P>
"I want to have a proposal laid out in the State of the Union
to expand the quality and portability of child care," Clinton said
on ABC's "Good Morning America."
</P>
<P>
The Clintons are holding a conference today focusing on the
issues of cost and quality of child care without offering any
sweeping federal initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The challenge is to boost quality without increasing the price
tag.
</P>
<P>
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton called day care a "silent
crisis" and urged states and local communities to find solutions.
</P>
<P>
"Every national survey demonstrates what we have to recognize:
Too much of our child care is not adequate. There are too many
situations that don't even meet basic standards," said Mrs.
Clinton on "Good Morning America."
</P>
<P>
The president added that he wants businesses to help employees
secure child care and schools to keep their buildings open after
classes.
</P>
<P>
During a preview of the conference for reporters Wednesday, the
first lady said any program for improving child care should
include help for stay-at-home moms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
