<HEADLINE> Syria: Primakov's Visit Aims to Save Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeni Primakov's forthcoming visit to Syria, due to start next
Saturday, is intended to save the stumbling Middle East peace
process, Syria's official SANA news agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's Mideast tour which will also take him to Lebanon,
Israel, Jordan, Egypt and the Gaza Strip, the agency quoted Syrian
official sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the sources said, is a fresh effort by Russia -- a
co-sponsor of the Middle East peace process along with the U.S. --
to save and stimulate the peace process which has been in a crisis
blamed on Israel's hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
Russian Ambassador to Damascus Victor Goguitidze announced
Wednesday evening that Primakov's forthcoming visit to Syria is
designed to contribute to the efforts to revive the Middle East
peace process, to promote Russian-Syrian bilateral ties and to
examine some international issues.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ambassador called for resuming the Syrian-Israeli
peace talks from the point at which they came to a halt on the
basis of the 1991 Madrid conference principles, the principle of
land-for-peace, and the U.N. Security Council resolutions 242,
338 and 425, which demand Israel's withdrawal from the occupied
Arab territories.


=10231548
