<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Team Arrives in Guilin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A team of US experts is
preparing to reexamine the wreckage of a US B-24 bomber that
crashed during the Second World War in south China.
</P>
<P>
The team organized by the US Defense Department, arrived this
afternoon in Guilin, a picturesque city in southwest China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the team will visit the crash site in a forest in
Xing'an County, located some 100 km from Guilin.
</P>
<P>
In January, members of the first team identified the wreckage
of the B-24 bomber and verified the remains of some crewmen. A
short time later, China held ceremonies to officially hand over
the recovered remains of crewmen to the team.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, two Xing'an farmers discovered the wreckage while
searching for medical herbs in a thick forest.
</P>
<P>
The current team sent a seven-member advance group to Guangxi
on October 16 to locate and pinpoint the exact location of the
crash site.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources say the second search will require 15-20 days
and will most likely be concluded by the middle of November. China
will fully cooperate with the U.S. team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
