<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: One 10th TB Cases Resists Common Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- About one in 10 new cases of
tuberculosis worldwide is resistant to at least one of the common
drugs used to treat the disease, according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by four health agencies from 1994 to
1997. Tuberculosis bacteria were sampled in 35 countries, or
regions of countries.
</P>
<P>
TB may soon become difficult or impossible to treat, The
Washington Post said today, quoting Sally A. Shelton-Colby, an
official of the U.S. Agency for International Development (AID).
</P>
<P>
"If tuberculosis were a new disease, the world would spare no
expense to fight it," said Arata Kochi, director of TB programs
for the World Health Organization (WHO), which helped organize
the study. "Now, while we have been looking the other way..., the
germ has mutated into drug-resistant strains, making itself a more
difficult and deadly enemy to combat."
</P>
<P>
Tuberculosis is the most common serious infectious disease in
the world. About 7 million new cases, and slightly more than 2
million deaths, occur each year, the Post report said.
</P>
<P>
The study found that in Latvia, 34 percent of new cases are
resistant to at least one drug, and 14 percent are resistant to
the drugs isoniazid and rifampin. In Thailand, the resistance is
37 percent and 4 percent, respectively. And in the Dominican
Republic, it is 41 percent and 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Drug-resistant strains of the bacterium almost always arise
from strains that were survived incomplete or inadequate courses
of therapy. The survey found that among TB patients who had
undergone some treatment, the prevalence of drug-resistant
bacteria was 36 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
