<HEADLINE> Chinese, Norwegian Foreign Ministers Confer in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen held talks today with Norwegian
Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers praised the bilateral relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that bilateral ties have witnessed constant
development since the two nations established diplomatic relations
some 43 years ago. He also pointed to highly-beneficial economic,
trade, scientific and technological, and cultural cooperation in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit to
Norway last year and the current visit by Norwegian King Harald V
have played an important role in promoting friendly bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He told Vollebaek that China places great importance on its
relations with Norway, and pointed to the absence of conflicts in
basic interests between the two countries. Qian said the two
countries share identical or similar viewpoints on many
international issues. "No major obstacles prevent the two sides
from engaging in mutually beneficial cooperation," said Qian.
</P>
<P>
China has consistently maintained that all countries, large or
small, poor or rich, or strong or weak, are equal in the
international community, and each can make its own efforts to
promote world peace and development, said Qian.
</P>
<P>
Different points of views on some issues are understandable due
to the differing national characteristics of China and Norway,
Qian noted. This is the very reason that the two countries should
further increase contacts, enhance mutual understanding and deepen
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that joint efforts will ensure that bilateral
relations continue to grow in a sound manner," said Qian.
</P>
</TEXT>
