<HEADLINE> Chinese, Norwegian Foreign Ministers Hold Talks in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vollebaek underlined the fact that Norway was in the first
group of Western nations to recognize the People's Republic of
China, and that Norwegian people admire China's development over
the past 20 years. He particularly praised China for solving
problems related to feeding and clothing its 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said Norway hopes to promote Sino-Norwegian
relations, and noted that China is playing an increasingly
important role in the region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian government is fully prepared to expand friendly
and cooperative ties with China, said Vollebaek, noting that the
Norwegian government's policy is to adhere to its "one China"
stance and refrain from forging official links with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the two countries have engaged in active exchanges on
the human rights issue, and that China proposes to deal with
differences concerning the human rights issue on the basis of
equality and mutual respect, and to practice a policy of
cooperation rather than confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Dialog and cooperation between China and Norway, and other
countries, will help to enhance mutual understanding on the human
rights issue, according to Qian.
</P>
<P>
Qian and Vollebaek agreed that the two foreign ministries will
hold consultations concerning the affairs of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also conferred on the international
situation, as well as the current situation in the Asia-Pacific
Region and Europe. 
</P>
