<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Stays Firm on Climate Change Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Australia today remained firm
on its climate change stance and rejected a United States proposal
to stabilize greenhouse gas emissions, despite it being the most
lenient suggestion put forward by its most important political and
economic allies so far.
</P>
<P>
Australia is now isolated from three major trading partners,
the United States, Japan and the European Union, over the
greenhouse gas emission reduction issue.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, the United States called for industrial nations to
fight global warming by stabilizing their emissions of greenhouse
gases at 1990 levels by between 2008 and 2012, and reducing
emissions after that.
</P>
<P>
While the position is far more lenient than the EU's call for a
15 percent reduction in emissions from the 1990 levels by 2010, it
has already been rejected by Australian Prime Minister John
Howard.
</P>
<P>
Japan put forward a proposal earlier this month for a five
percent cut in emission from the 1990 levels by about 2010.
</P>
<P>
Howard told a business dinner earlier this month that
stabilizing emissions at the 1990 levels by 2010 would put at risk
about 48 billion US dollars worth of investment in the energy and
mining sector over the next five years and cost tens of thousands
of new jobs.
</P>
<P>
And Australian Environment Minister Robert Hill said today the
US position would be too costly for Australia.
</P>
<P>
"That figure couldn't be achieved by Australia without
significant economic sacrifice and job losses," Hill told
reporters here.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, there was a lot in (U.S. President Bill Clinton's)
speech that seems remarkably similar to the sort of things that
we've been saying."
</P>
<P>
Australia is arguing that any reduction targets agreed to at a
major summit in Kyoto, Japan, in December should take into account
different countries' economic circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said the three different
climate change plans put forward by Europe, Japan and now the U.S.
proved Australia's model was the only workable solution.
</P>
<P>
Kinza Clodumar, president of Nauru, today denounced Australia's
stand on greenhouse gas emissions and called for Japan and France
to fill the leadership vacuum left by Australia in the South
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Clodumar said the issue of climate change, which virtually
split this year's South Pacific Forum, was the single most
important issue facing the region's mostly low-lying island
states.
</P>
<P>
"The Forum communique which emerged at the end of the meeting
was extremely bland and was painted by Australia, certainly by its
officials and Howard himself, as something of a victory," Clodumar
was quoted by the Australian Associated Press as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
