<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Windsurfer Faces Challenge at HK Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Olympic champion
windsurfer Lee Lai Shan faces a tough challenge from other
entrants at the 1997 Hong Kong Open Windsurfing Championships
which opened here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Competing in the three-day event are windsurfers from China's
national and Guangdong teams and from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), Germany, Poland, Japan, Thailand and
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Amelie Lux from Germany, 20, a two-time world youth
championship winner, said it is very hot and humid here, compared
with the cool and rainy days back in her hometown in Kiel, in
north Germany.
</P>
<P>
"I had some trouble with the weather, too," she said. There
had been no strong wind in recent days over the race course off
the Cheung Chau Island, site of the competition. Local weather
forecast predicts strong wind around the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"Let's wait and pray for good weather," she joked.
</P>
<P>
Joining her here was 23-year-old Pole Anna Galecka, winner at
the national championships last September and seventh placer at
this year's European championships.
</P>
<P>
A veteran windsurfer for the last nine years, Galecka said: "I
like the windsurfing as it is a very good sport. In the sport, I
could travel many places in the world and make friends as well,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Amid the field for the event are China's Asia-Pacific
championships bronze-medalist Liu Youcai and his teammate and
national champion from this year's national games Chen Zhanying.
</P>
<P>
Also in the field are Thailand's Homrdrusn Arun, winner at the
Hiroshima Asian Games in 1994 and Hong Kong's Asian champion Wong
Tak Sum.
</P>
<P>
Hosts Hong Kong athletes had training for the past week. But
the lack of strong wind had forced them to abandon training for at
least three days.
</P>
<P>
Set on the program are International Raceboard Class and
International Mistral One Design Class, for heavy weight and light
weight events for both men and women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
