<HEADLINE> Manila, Labor Groups Fail to Resolve Wage Controversy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the country's labor leaders failed today to reach an agreement on
the matter of wage increases after a seven-hour closed-door
meeting at the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The Tripartite Consultation on Wage and Productivity, attended
by representatives from various labor groups, employers'
associations and key government officials led by President Fidel
Ramos, ended with a decision to leave the matter to the Regional
Wage Boards.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Ramos ordered the National Wages and
Productivity Commission to undertake a complete review of existing
wages granted by the Regional Wage Boards and to act expeditiously
on all pending petitions for minimum wage adjustments.
</P>
<P>
He also directed Labor Secretary Leonardo Quisumbing to review
and report any developments on the action taken along the wage
hike issue till November 21.
</P>
<P>
However, labor leaders felt disappointed over the results of
the meeting as it failed to secure its desired across-the-board
wage hike.
</P>
<P>
"We were dissatisfied because all of our requests were not
addressed," said Democrito Mondozo, president of the moderate
Trade Union Congress of the Philippines, after emerging from the
meeting which labor leaders expected to grant workers a legislated
wage increase.
</P>
<P>
Quisumbing said there were some form of a "consensus" among the
participants to the consultation "that the wage boards' action
must go on to determine the wage increases."
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was precipitated by the recent peso devaluation
and the series of oil price adjustments which triggered increases
in the prices of prime commodities.
</P>
<P>
Labor leaders have been pressing the government for another
round of wage increases.
</P>
<P>
However, Miguel Varela, president of the Employers
Confederation of the Philippines, said that according to the law,
the Regional Wage Boards is the one that will fix any pay hike.
</P>
<P>
He said the minimum increase will be determined by the boards
and several factors will be considered.  
</P>
</TEXT>
