<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Reacts Strongly to Clinton's Emission Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
commissioner for environment today expressed disappointment on the
greenhouse gas emissions plan announced by the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I am disappointed with the very weak level of ambition of the
United States," an EU press release quoted Commissioner Ritt
Bjerregaard as saying, as his first reaction to the U.S. plan.
</P>
<P>
"This is not an adequate response to the global problems of
climate change," said Bjerregaard.
</P>
<P>
At a speech on Wednesday in Washington, U.S. President Bill
Clinton called on gradual and mandatory reduction in so-called
greenhouse gases to curb the threat of global warming.
</P>
<P>
Under Clinton's plan, the U.S. industries are to reduce carbon
emissions to the 1990 levels over the next 12 years.
</P>
<P>
But the convention on climate change, adopted at the Earth
Summit in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, in 1992, has already urged
emission stabilization by the year 2000 at the 1990 levels for
industrialized countries, said the EU commissioner.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton said four years ago that through voluntary
efforts the United States could cut carbon emissions to the 1990
levels by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
However, emissions have been growing and are now expected to
exceed the 1990 levels by 13 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. position to reach this goal by sometime around 2010
is therefore a significant step in the wrong direction," said
Bjerregaard.
</P>
<P>
The EU, which has called for a 15 percent cut in greenhouse gas
emissions from their 1990 levels, also attacked a Japanese plan
calling for a 5 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
The union's negotiating position on a 15 percent reduction is
technically feasible and economically manageable, the commissioner
reaffirmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Loans for Xiaolangdi Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAOLANGDI, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has since
October 1994 provided loans of 553.4 million US dollars for
construction of the Xiaolangdi multi-purpose water conservancy
project, the largest of its kind on the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The project, second only to the Three Gorges Dam Project,
is the largest water conservancy project China has constructed
with loans from the World Bank. Half of the 1.16 billion US dollar
loan for the Xiaolangdi Project has already been put to use.
</P>
<P>
World Bank officials have expressed satisfaction with the rate
of progress, quality and resettlement efforts, and rate the
project as an exemplary example in the use of loans.
</P>
<P>
The project has tendered construction bids from across the
world, with three prestigious foreign hydraulic engineering
companies which have won bids forming three joint operations with
Chinese engineering companies.
</P>
<P>
The river will be dammed on October 28 and the overall project
is expected to be completed in the year 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
