<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Situation Stable, Says Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- China's financial situation was
stable in the first three quarters of this year marked mainly by
appropriate growth in the money supply, the People's Bank of China
said today.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics of the central bank show that the
outstanding value of broad money, known as M2, which is the
combination of cash in circulation plus all sorts of deposits,
stood at 8,589.24 billion yuan by the end of September, up 17.1
percent from a year ago and down 8.2 percentage points from the
end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding amount of narrow money, or M1, which is the
combination of cash in circulation plus the demand deposits of
enterprises, was valued at 3,224.46 billion yuan by the end of
last month, an increase of 17.3 percent from the comparable figure
of last year and a drop of 1.6 percentage points from the amount
at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of cash in circulation, or M0, rose 12.1 percent from
a year ago to 942.61 billion yuan by the end of September. Cash
supply in the first nine months reached 62.41 billion yuan, 10.05
billion yuan more than that for the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that outstanding deposits at the banking
system were valued at 7,831.3 billion yuan by the end of last
month, 18 percent more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The central bank noted that due to the increase in direct
financing, larger treasury bond issuance and diversification of
personal financial assets, the expansion of individual savings has
slowed down since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, personal savings were valued at
4,413.95 billion yuan, up 18.1 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The value of outstanding loans totaled 7,056.45 billion yuan by
last month, a rise of 17.1 percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Official figures indicate that China's foreign exchange
reserves grew by 29 billion US dollars in the first three quarters
of this year to more than 134 billion US dollars by the end of
last month.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that, considering the present situation,
it will continue to follow a moderately tight monetary policy and
conduct proper economic macro-control so as to ensure steady
growth of the national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
