<HEADLINE> HK's Foreign Reserves Up in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) announced today that the official foreign
exchange reserves of Hong Kong were 88.1 billion US dollars at the
end of September, up 3.3 percent from the end of August.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is now the world's third largest holder of foreign
reserves after Japan and China's interior areas.
</P>
<P>
The increase in foreign reserves represents mainly a rise in
the foreign currency component of the Exchange Fund and the Land
Fund, said the HKMA, the de facto central bank in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
As of the end of September, the foreign reserves held in the
Exchange Fund were 71.4 billion and those in the Land Fund were
16.7 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Including outstanding forward transactions, the foreign
reserves held in the Exchange Fund and the Land Fund were 71.7
billion US dollars and 17.1 billion US dollars respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
