<HEADLINE> Russian Reaps 94 Million Tons of Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia has harvested 94 million
metric tons of grain by October 20, up 26.3 percent over the same
period last year, the Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Former collective farms and state farms, which manage over 90
percent of the country's crop land, have got in 84.4 million tons
of grain against 68.1 million by the same period last year,
</P>
<P>
The per hectare yield is 2.26 tons, a 0.31 ton increase from
last year, the State Statistics Committee was quoted as saying,
adding most of the harvest work is now taking place in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
As of October 20, the committee said, 1 million tons of corn,
up 500,000 tons from the same period last year, has been harvested
from 4.5 million hectares, 1.1 million less than last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian farmers have gathered in 7.8 million tons of
sugarbeet, down from 13.1 million tons in 1996; and 1.2 million
tons of sunflower seeds, down from 1.9 million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The government statistics agency said winter crops to be
harvested in 1998 had been sown on 12.5 million hectares, 1.7
percent less than this year.
</P>
<P>
In total, it said, 27.9 million hectares of land has been
plowed for spring sowing, down from 33.2 million hectares last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
