<HEADLINE> Trade Control System Works Well in HK: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government is doing all it can to
ensure that its effective trade control system works and that the
interests of its legitimate traders are protected, a local
official said today.
</P>
<P>
"As enshrined in the Basic Law, the HKSAR remains a separate
customs territory after the transition," Hong Kong
Director-General of Trade Alan Lai told the general session on
customs and trade at the New York State Bar Association Conference
being held here.
</P>
<P>
"The integrity of our trade control system is the cornerstone
of our separate customs territory status," he said.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR takes its international obligations under the World
Trade Organization (WTO) Agreement on Textiles and Clothing
seriously and maintains the utmost vigilance over attempts to
abuse origin rules, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lai said that the HKSAR has an effective system to deal with
the problem of illegal transshipment, particularly with a series
of new initiatives introduced in the past two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
Such initiatives include factory audit checks introduced in
November 1996 and the integrated consignment and factory
inspection introduced in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
On control over strategic commodities, a minute was signed in
Hong Kong earlier this month by US Secretary of Commerce William
Daley and Hong Kong Secretary for Trade and Industry Miss Denise
Yue, he noted.
</P>
<P>
It is in HKSAR's interest to maintain effective controls over
strategic commodities trade because only by doing so can the HKSAR
 have free access to sophisticated goods and technologies
essential for Hong Kong's economic development, Lai quoted Miss
Yue as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
