<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tension Still High in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Tension remained high today in
the southern Philippine island of Mindanao as government troops
failed to withdraw from areas near a stronghold of a major rebel
group as promised earlier, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
Muhamad al-Haj Murad, vice chairman of the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF), told the local ABS-CBN television that
the government troops had failed to pull back from those towns
surrounding its bastion, Camp Abubakar, in Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
He said tension was still high around the camp as a result of
the military's failure to reposition its forces as promised at an
emergency meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The positions being occupied by the rebels and the government
troops in the area are only two to four kilometers away from each
other.
</P>
<P>
At the emergency meeting Tuesday, peace panels from the
government and the MILF agreed to respect an earlier preliminary
truce and reposition their respective forces in order to defuse
rising tension in central Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
In exchange for the withdrawal of the government troops, the
rebels agreed to stop public execution of people they themselves
find guilty.
</P>
<P>
Also today, a senior military officer said there is no need for
the government troops to move away from the outskirts of three
towns surrounding the rebels' bastion since they have not moved
"even an inch" closer to it.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the Philippine News Agency, Maj. Gen. Raul Urgello,
commander of the Army's Sixth Infantry Division, said his troops
have not "encroached" MILF tolerated areas so there is no reason
for them to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
But Urgello said if ordered by the higher command for them to
pull out or reduce government forces in the area, they will do so
to appease MILF's apprehension that the military will attack Camp
Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has accused the military of preparing to seize
Abubakar, the rebels' biggest camp in Mindanao, by building up
troops in its nearby areas. But the military denied the charge,
saying the troop movement was a routine redeployment.
</P>
<P>
But the troops' build-up was widely believed to be in
retaliation for the rebels' public execution of two alleged
criminals early this month, who were convicted by a rebel court.
</P>
<P>
Boasting a membership of more than 20,000, the MILF now has the
largest number of anti-government troops in the country. It has
fought for a separate Islamic state in Mindanao since the late
1970s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
