<HEADLINE> Mealie-meal Price Hike Condemned in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The recent hike on the price of
mealie meal will severely erode the buying power of the already
poverty-stricken consumers battling with high prices, the
Consumer Council of Zimbabwe (CCZ) said today.
</P>
<P>
''The 36 percent hike on maize is just excessive and is not
sustainable to consumers considering that most consumers are
poverty-stricken,'' the CCZ said.
</P>
<P>
The council said consumers were already burdened with high
prices of other goods such as bread and cooking oil and high
rates for social services.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the increases, the CCZ said consumers should
take their maize to hammer-millers.
</P>
<P>
''Not only is maize-meal ground at hammer mills cheaper but it
is even nutritious,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
''The government should have in place a mechanism for
cushioning vulnerable consumers form increases in the price of
basic goods and services,'' the CCZ said.
</P>
<P>
Mealie-meal prices went up by 36 percent with effect from
Monday. The price of bread will go up by between 7.5 percent and
10 percent as from October 27.
</P>
<P>
Millers said the latest increase was caused by the need to pay
farmers and traders who are demanding a higher price for their
maize.
</P>
<P>
The Grain Marketing Board increased its buying price in order
to attract sellers to beef up its maize reserve in the face of a
looming drought in the 1997/98 season.
</P>
<P>
Price of maize at the Zimbabwe Agricultural Commodity Exchange
has also increased in the past week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
