<HEADLINE> ADB Helps Asian Countries Fight AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said today it will support the 4th International Congress on AIDS
in Asia and the Pacific, to be held here from October 25 to 29,
with a grant of 100,000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,500 people are expected to attend the congress, which
has the theme of "Partnerships Across Borders Against HIV/AIDS."
The meeting is held every two years and is the largest of its type
is Asia.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is also providing 150,000 US dollar in technical
assistance to help countries in the Great Mekong Subregion in the
control and prevention of HIV/AIDS by supplementing national
approaches at the subregional level.
</P>
<P>
The Great Mekong Subregion encompasses Cambodia, Yunnan
province of China, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS epidemic is one of the most serious threats to the
social and physical well-being of peoples in Asia and can have a
major adverse impact on economic development.
</P>
<P>
All Asian countries are at risk, and prevalence is particularly
high in Thailand, Myanmar, Cambodia and Vietnam, according to some
data. In India, the minimum number of HIV cases was placed at two
million in mid-1996.  
</P>
