<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Project Open to Equipment Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- China will import at least one
billion US dollars worth of equipment from the United States for
the Three Gorges Project, according to a project official.
</P>
<P>
Imports will mainly include equipment for concrete mixing and
pouring, and high-voltage transmission lines and transformers, said
Wang Jiazhu, vice-president of the China Yangtze River Project
Three Gorges Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the Chinese government fully supports the Three
Gorges Project will provide US businesspeople with a golden
opportunity, and we sincerely hope US ventures will actively enter
the international bidding process," according to the
vice-president.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that at least two to three billion US Dollars worth
of equipment imports will be required for the massive earth and
stone work and pouring of concrete once the mainstream of the
Yangtze River is dammed in early November.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that imports will account for at least half
of the equipment for the Three Gorges Project, with 70 percent of
same coming from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Wang said that his corporation will actively seek
overseas financial backing to overcome fund shortages of 39
billion yuan prior to the year 2006.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome export credits, commercial loans and loans from
overseas financial institutions," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project, the world's largest water control
project, will involve construction of the world's largest power
plant, lock system and 2,300 m x 185 m dam. The massive project
will be constructed at an estimated cost of 25 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 25 percent of total funds will be used to
purchase more than 30,000 types of construction materials and
machinery.
</P>
<P>
A large majority of the equipment will be imported from the
United States, with other machinery coming from Japan, Sweden,
Germany and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The bid process considers competitively priced high technology,
with preferential export credits considered to be an important
aspect for those winning contracts, said Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
