<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Refugee Foundation Moves to Clothe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- African Refugees Foundation
(AREF), a Nigeria-based humanitarian organization has launched an
operation to help clothe African refugees, its President and
founder, Chief Segun Olusola, announced in Lagos today.
</P>
<P>
The program, dubbed "African Garments for African Refugees",
is designed to establish a process of continuous production and
stocking of culturally appropriate garments for African refugees,
Olusola said at a forum organized by the Pan African News Agency
and the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Such clothes, he said, would make it easier for refugees to
re-integrate into the society, because they use textiles and
designs made for Africa's weather conditions and are more
culturally sensitive.
</P>
<P>
Olusola said the idea of the program was first conceived in
1994, when AREF airlifted culturally appropriate garments to
Rwandan refugees and received great admiration of the Rwandans as
well as other international relief agencies.
</P>
<P>
According to him, AREF has established a production base at
the headquarters of the Nigerian Red Cross Society and has got
the first designs from the Society of Nigerian Artists.
</P>
<P>
Some of the designs were shown at the forum.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged the receipt of a donation of two million Naira
(about 24,000 U.S. Dollars) for the execution of the program from
the Shell Petroleum Development Company of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Olusola had served as Nigeria's Ambassador to Ethiopia and its
resident representative to the Organization of African Unity
(OAU). He was the chairman of the refugees commission of fifteen
on refugees from 1988 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
He set up the AREF upon his retirement in 1993. Since then, he
explained, AREF has been involved in relief programs in Rwanda,
Somalia and Nigeria. It has also been sponsoring studies of the
refugee issue in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Olusola expressed concern at the unending conflicts and
refugees issues in Africa. He estimated that there are about six
to seven million refugees and three times of that of displaced
persons across the continent.
</P>
<P>
Noting that many of Africa's conflicts arise from power
struggle between ethnic groups, he advocated the culture of power
sharing and ethnic tolerance.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for both governmental and
non-governmental organizations to evolve more effective conflict
management and prevention mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, our efforts now, particularly at the governmental
level, must shift from conflict management and resolution to
conflict prevention through the use of timely dialogue," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
