<HEADLINE> US Businesses Have High Expectations for Jiang Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Major US companies with offices
in China have expressed hope that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
forthcoming state visit to the United States will be successful
and fuel expanded economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
During a recent interview with Xinhua, representatives of
Chinese subsidiaries of Boeing, IBM, Microsoft, Motorola, Ford,
Coca-Cola, Visa, United Technologies and DuPont said that stable
political ties between China and the US will ensure the success of
economic and trade cooperation and will encourage US firms to
invest more in China.
</P>
<P>
They said that their companies will work to help improve and
develop Sino-US relations.
</P>
<P>
Michael Zimmerman, president of Boeing China Inc., commented
that Sino-US relations are improving in the wake of period of
uncertainty. He said President Jiang's visit will be extremely
important for the further development of Sino-US political and
economic ties, and will increase Boeing's confidence in its future
development prospects in the country.
</P>
<P>
IBM (China) Chairman Henry Chow said that improved Sino-US
relations will encourage American businesspeople with investment
in China to expand their operations.
</P>
<P>
He said that strengthened relations will ensure the smooth
business development of large companies like IBM.
</P>
<P>
P.Y. Lai, president of Motorola (China) Electronics Ltd., said
that sound commercial links are indispensable for the steady
development of Sino-US relations despite certain unfavorable
factors. He said his company has always placed priority on
promoting bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Visa International Vice-President and Chief Representative to
China Lee Leehun said that China's steady economic development
serves as a true indicator that the country has been transformed
from a potential to an actual huge market.
</P>
<P>
The change offers tremendous opportunities for cooperation
between China and other countries, said Lee.
</P>
<P>
Paul Wong, general manager of DuPont China company, said time
is ripe for DuPont to expand its business in China.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese government support has enabled DuPont to
enjoy vigorous development, gain a large market share, and join
trade partners with common goals.
</P>
<P>
Richard Latham, president of international operations for China
United Technologies Corp., praised his Chinese staff as being
diligent and highly educated.
</P>
<P>
Latham noted that 20 investment analysts visited China in
September along with UTC Chairman George David. He said Latham
attributed UTC's subsequent three-point gain on the New York Stock
Exchange to the analysts "favorable assessment" of the work
discipline, education level of Chinese employees, and quality of
both Chinese products and management.
</P>
<P>
Steve Chan, general manager of Coca-Cola China, said the
Chinese government's policies regarding the reform of China's
state-owned enterprises, and the encouraging rise in investments
in central and western China, have offered good opportunities for
foreign businesses to develop in the Chinese market. 
</P>
