<HEADLINE> Mandela Ends Visit to Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela left Tripoli this morning after a two-day visit to Libya,
the Libyan official news agency JANA reported.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference before his departure, Mandela declared
that he came to Libya to thank Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi and
the Libyan people for their support to South Africa and also to extend
help to the Libyans in regards to the U.N. sanctions on Libya.
</P>
<P>
This was Mandela's first visit to Libya since he became
president of South Africa in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said that he had talks Wednesday night with Gaddafi on
ways of developing bilateral ties and a number of issues of
mutual concern, particularly African ones.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, the South African president called for an
end to the U.N. sanctions on Libya, which were imposed in
1992 after Libya failed to hand over two men suspected of bombing
a Pan Am jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, killing 270
people on board.
</P>
<P>
Mandela drove into Libya Wednesday from neighboring Tunisia to
avoid violating the U.N. sanctions which banned arms sales and
flights in and out of the north African country.
</P>
<P>
His tour to Egypt, Tunisia and Libya was aimed at exchanging
views with leaders of these countries on regional and
international issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Libya had supported Mandela-led African National Congress
morally, financially and militarily during its 25 years of
struggle against the white-minority rule in South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
