<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment in Steel Production Falls Sharply Over 1975-96 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Employment by the steel industry
of industrialized Western nations dropped sharply over 1975-1996,
the International Labor Organization (ILO) said today.
</P>
<P>
The number of job positions in steel production in the European
Union (EU) countries fell by 67 percent from 991,000 in 1975 to
326,000 in 1995, said a report released here by the ILO.
</P>
<P>
From 1975 to 1996, France registered a loss of 75 percent from
157,000 to 38,500 jobs while the United Kingdom's employment in
the industry slid by 80 percent from 190,700 to 37,000, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, noted the report entitled the Iron and Steel
Workforce of the 21st Century, steel production in the two
countries fell by 16 and 14 percent respectively over the period.
</P>
<P>
The workforce in the U.S. and Japanese steel industries shrank
by about half from 470,400 to 237,500 and from 324,400 to 155,000
respectively, while their output fell by 10 percent and 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, labor will continue to play an important role in steel
production despite improvement in technology.
</P>
<P>
"The human dimension is the key to the future," said the ILO
report, adding that "technical advances are short-lived."
</P>
<P>
"Successful steelmaking in the 21st century will depend more
than ever on an enduring but responsive and flexible partnership
between the enterprise and its workforce," it asserted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
