<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
weaker today after a "wild and whippy" session, suffering from a
crisis of confidence in the wake of the Asian currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
After plummeting to a three-and-a-half year low, the local
currency drew little comfort from new data which damped down the
prospect of a rate cut here in the short term.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange market is nervous and players fear the
Australian dollar has further to fall.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 70.68 US cents, from a close
yesterday of 71.21.
</P>
<P>
Worries that Australia will be drawn into the economic turmoil
of Southeast Asia dragged the Australian dollar down to 70.45 US
cents, a level not seen since May 1994, in early morning dealings.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the local currency was reacting to reports, mainly
from US investment banks, that the Australian economy was at risk
from the economic woes of its neighbors. Some of those reports
have advised investors to "get out of" Australian and New Zealand
currencies.
</P>
<P>
ANZ head of foreign exchange sales John Reedyk said the market
was nervous and jittery.
</P>
<P>
At close tonight, the Australian dollar was at 85.89 yen from
85.51 yesterday, and against the Deutsche mark it was at 1.2639,
from 1.2739. 
</P>
</TEXT>
