<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA President Arafat Leaves for Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat left Gaza today for a
European tour, which will take him to France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day visit, Arafat is scheduled to hold talks
with French and German leaders on issues concerning the Middle
East peace talks and ask them to render assistance in pushing the
peace process forward, according to the Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian news service said Arafat will also visit the
Hague, where he will address a European Union conference on recent
developments of the Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, both the United States peace envoy Dennis
Ross and the European Union (EU) peace mediator Miguel Moratinos
intensified their shuttle mediation between Israel and the PNA in
a bid to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a meeting between Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Ross also organized a meeting on
Monday between Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy and PNA deputy
head Abu Mazen in an attempt to bridge the gap between the two
sides over the PNA demand for a halt to Israeli settlement
expansion and the Israeli request for a tougher PNA fight against
terror.
</P>
<P>
Arafat met Moratinos at the West Bank city of Ramallah on
Monday, agreeing to accept the EU proposal that Israel and PNA
adopt a code of conduct to restore mutual confidence.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and PNA negotiating teams are to meet in Washington by
the end of this month to discuss Israeli troop redeployments,
Israel's halt of settlement activities, the security concepts and
ways of starting the final-status negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
