<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Athletes Achieve Promising Results in Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 23 (Xinhua) -- As the track and field
competitions concluded on Thursday, the Chinese athletes have
displayed their top forms by bettering one world record in the
women's 5,000 meters and breaking five Asian records at the Eighth
National Games.
</P>
<P>
Both Jiang Bo, 20, and Dong Yanmei, 17, clocked their world
record-breaking marks in the last-day's 5,000 meters to salute the
local enthusiastic fans.
</P>
<P>
The two women runners of Liaoning province clocked 14:28.09 and
14:29.82 respectively for a one-two finish, completing the Chinese
sweep of all world records in the women's long-distance events.
</P>
<P>
"It's a glory for Liaoning, and also a glory for all the
Chinese people," said famous track coach Ma Junren.
</P>
<P>
The former record of 14:31.27 was set by Dong Yanmei in the
heats on Tuesday, which beat the original mark of 14:36.45 set by
Fernanda Ribeiro of Portugal in Hechtel, Belgium on July 22, 1995.
</P>
<P>
And both Jiang Bo and Dong Yanmei became double champions from
the track as Jiang clocked three minutes 50.98 seconds to take her
first title in the women's 1,500 meters and Dong timed in 30:38.09
to take the 10,000 meters on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Another woman phenomynon also stunned the Chinese audience by
taking both the 100-meter and 200-meter national titles, all with
Asian marks.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuemei broke the 100m mark twice en route to her victory.
The 20-year-old Li first timed in 10.90 seconds in the heats and
later claimed the national title in 10.79, all overpassing the
original Asian mark of 11.02 set by Liu Xiaomei four years ago in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Sichuan woman sprinter succeeded in beating
the second Asian mark in the 200 meters wherein she timed in 22.01
seconds. The previous mark of 22.39 was set by Susanthika
Jayasinghe of Sri Lanka in the World Athletics Championships in
August.
</P>
<P>
Both Li Xuemei and Liu Xiaomei then paced the Sichuan squad for
another national title by breaking their third Asian record,
clocking 42.23 seconds in the women's 4x100 meters.
</P>
<P>
Another Asian record was set up in the women's 400-meter
hurdles when Jiang Limei of Guangxi timed in 53.38 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Woman long jumper Xiong Qiying of Sichuan leapt to a distance
of 7.03 meters in the qualifying rounds to beat the original Asian
mark of 7.01 meters.22.39 set by Susanthika Jayasinghe of Sri
Lanka in the World Athletics Championships in August.
</P>
<P>
As the athletes packed up their luggages for departure, Chinese
track officials encourged them to keep their forms in order to
attain more achievements in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Our athletes have to demonstrate their strengths in the world
and the National Games only serves as a training ground for them
to accumulate experiences," said a top sports official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
