<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAHRF Raises $50m to Fight Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Human
Rights Foundation (SAHRF) has set aside a funding of 50
million U.S. dollars for the eradication of poverty in the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) region, Times of
Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by SAHRF Executive Director Achibald Ngcobo
in a paper he presented at a three-day national micro-credit
summit which opened in Lusaka Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ngecobo told the meeting that the fund will be distributed at
a ratio of about 3 million to 5.2 million per country, depending
on various factors such as population, size, and income levels.
</P>
<P>
The initial funding is for a period of three years starting
from July 1998 up to 2001, Ngecobo noted.
</P>
<P>
He drew the meeting's attention to the deprivation of poverty
and destitution that has reached unprecedented levels in the SADC
region after the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank introduced the structural adjustment programs (SAP) in early
1990s in the continent.
</P>
<P>
SAHRF will ensure that issues of empowering the vulnerable
groups in the region become center-stage, Ngecobo added.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that empowerment of the poor will only
succeed if it has its strength in the rural areas and does not
create a dependency syndrome among the people.
</P>
<P>
The executive director emphasised the need for micro-credit
institutions in the region to work in harmony and not in
isolation or in competition so as to realise the dream of a
poverty free region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
