<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Plunges 2.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
plunged as much as 2.7 percent before recovering slightly to end
2.5 percent lower as massive Hong Kong-inspired selling swept
across Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Today's falls pushed up the Australian market's losses to more
than 4 percent in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed 68 points down at 2614.9.
</P>
<P>
"The weakness in the Asian markets and of course the big
markdown in Hong Kong just flowed through here significantly this
afternoon," Shaw Stockbrokings' Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
Stronger-than-expected local wages data, which reduced hopes
for another interest rate cut in the short term, also contributed
to the Australian market's fall but it was largely overshadowed by
the situation in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong bourse sank 14 percent in morning trading, its
largest percentage fall in 10 years, before closing 1,211 points,
or 10.4 percent, lower at 10,426.3.
</P>
<P>
The local market's next move is too tough to call and it is now
a case of waiting to see how U.S. and European markets would fare
overnight, Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index shed 91 points, or 2.05 percent, to
4353.5 while the All Resources lost 52.3 points, or 4.04 percent,
to 1240.9.
</P>
<P>
Sliding Asian currencies would hamper economic growth, delaying
demand for commodities, sapping commodity prices and weighing on
domestic resources shares for a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP tumbled 88 cents, or 5.9 percent, to 14
Australian dollars, its lowest level in about four years. Global
mining company Rio Tinto shed 1.066 Australian dollars, or 5.3
percent, to 19.15 Australian dollars and WMC fell 45 cents, or
7.68 percent, to 5.41 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The industrials performed better on the whole, with News Corp's
ordinary shares slipping 5.8 cents to 6.9 Australian dollars and
its preferred shares easing 1 to 6.19 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
But interest rate-sensitive banks did poorly, with NAB falling
62 cents, or 2.9 percent, to 20.75 Australian dollars; ANZ 44.5
cents, or 4.1 percent, to 10.41 Australian dollars; CBA 39.4 cents
to 16.436 Australian dollars and Westpac 3.3 cents to 8.783
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index lost 12.6 points to 1276.4, with gold bullion
closing at 323.65 U.S. dollars an ounce compared to 322.65 U.S.
dollars yesterday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 432.45 million shares valued at 1.289
 billion Australian dollars (915.19 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
