<HEADLINE> HK Chief Justice Named Honorary Bencher of Middle Temple in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Andrew Li, chief justice of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region's Court of Final
Appeal, was appointed as an Honorary Bencher of the Middle Temple
in London earlier today.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the court told reporters: "Apart from being a
personal honor for the chief justice, the appointment was a
recognition given to the status of the Hong Kong judiciary and its
standing in the common law jurisdictions."
</P>
<P>
Li has thus become the third person of Chinese ancestry given
such honor. The other two were the late Futting Tien-hsi Cheng,
former Judge of the Permanent Court of International Justice, who
was appointed Honorary Bencher of the Middle Temple in 1946, and
Singapore's former Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew who was similarly
honored in 1969.
</P>
<P>
The Middle Temple is one of the four Inns of Court in London.
There are currently 47 Honorary Benchers, among them are
distinguished judges and academics. The number of Honorary
Benchers is strictly limited and only a maximum of two are named
annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
