<HEADLINE> HKMA Opposes Repeated Borrowings by Licensed Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) said today that it opposes repeated borrowings by
licensed banks through the Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF)
amid concerns over the tumbling stocks here.
</P>
<P>
This is seen by experts here as a step taken by the local
monetary authorities for stabilizing the stock market which had
plummeted several days running.
</P>
<P>
The HKMA said in a statement that it "would like to remind
licensed banks that it does not encourage repeated borrowings by
licensed banks through the Liquidity Adjustment Facility (LAF)."
</P>
<P>
"Each licensed bank must organize their Hong Kong dollar
funding prudently and not be overly dependent upon the LAF for
last resort liquidity support," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In order to discourage licensed banks from repeated borrowings
from LAF, it continued, penal LAF offer rates different from the
advertised LAF offer rate will be determined on a case-by-case
basis and at the absolute discretion of the HKMA for repeated
borrowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
