<HEADLINE> Southeast Asia Currency Crisis Harms Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Southeast Asian currency
crisis could slash Australia's exports by up to 3 billion
Australian dollars (2.19 billion U.S. dollars) a year, the
National Farmers' Federation (NFF) said today.
</P>
<P>
NFF economic policy adviser Todd Ritchie said rough
calculations resulted in a 3 billion Australian dollar worst case
scenario.
</P>
<P>
"I've looked at how growth has been revised down and the impact
on Australian exports and growth," Ritchie said. "The result was
total exports down 1 billion to 3 billion Australian dollars
annually."
</P>
<P>
The currency crunch has hit just as farmers are hoping for
continued price increases in several key commodities.
</P>
<P>
Overseas agencies reported today that the currency crisis has
driven some feed and flour mill companies to the brink of collapse
while others are shying away from any buying until they have to.
</P>
<P>
But an Australian Wheat Board spokesman said customers from the
countries affected by the currency crisis indicated that they do
not expect the downturn to have a big impact on their wheat
purchases.
</P>
<P>
"Our customers have indicated at this stage they don't expect
to see significant changes in the level of their wheat
purchasers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics
analyst Terry Sheales said Australia's live cattle trade is
suffering under the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The trade, worth about 366 million Australian dollars (267
million U.S. dollars) last year, relies heavily on Southeast Asian
buyers.
</P>
<P>
Sheales said Indonesian importers are finding it difficult to
gain letters of credit due to the fluctuating value of the rupiah,
the country's currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
