<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Stand on Nigeria Remains, says Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- There will be no significant
change in all existing measures and sanctions imposed against
Nigeria by the U.S. until improvements are noticed to justify a
change, said William Twaddell, U.S. ambassador-designate to
Nigeria, said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been frosty since the
annulment of the June 12, 1993 presidential elections in Nigeria,
culminating in the imposition of limited sanctions on the
Nigerian military administration by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
There have been suggestions that the Bill Clinton
administration should go further by imposing an oil embargo on
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"We are considering ways to deploy more effectively the
panoply of normal diplomatic and other tools at our disposal to
influence developments in Nigeria," Twaddell told the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee which considered his nomination.
</P>
<P>
He said that Nigeria is too important to ignore. With more
than 100 million people and vast natural resources and economic
potential, Nigeria's capacity to influence regional developments,
for good or ill, is large, he added.
</P>
<P>
Instability in Nigeria would have profound humanitarian,
political and economic consequences for West Africa and other
regions, including the United States, he noted, adding that U.S.
interest in Nigeria are diverse.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Fundamentally, we seek a stable civilian democratic
government in Nigeria which respects human rights and the rule of
law."
</P>
<P>
"A priority U.S. government interest is combating Nigerian
criminal enterprises, narcotics trafficking and other activities
affecting the United States, and obtaining effective Nigerian
government cooperation to combat those menaces," Twaddell said.
</P>
<P>
The envoy also stated that as a practical matter, the United
States needed to continue to try to work with Nigerians on issues
of mutual concern to advance both short- and long-term
objectives.
</P>
<P>
Twaddell is said to have extensive experience in african
affairs, having served in Liberia, Mauritania, Guinea-Bissau and
Namibia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Producing Countries to Meet Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from 18 major
steel producing countries will meet here next week over the recent
and future changes in steel industry and their impact on the iron
and steel workforce.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from governments, trade unions and employer
organizations will meet from October 27 to 31 to discuss these
changes and their impact on the seven million workers currently
employed in the industry.
</P>
<P>
Countries to attend the meeting are Brazil, Canada, China, the
Czech Republic, France, Germany, India, Japan, the Republic of
Korea, Mexico, Poland, Romania, South Africa, Sweden, the United
Kingdom, the United States, Venezuela and Zimbabwe. Their steel
production combined accounts for three quarters of the world's
total.
</P>
<P>
The International Labor Organization (ILO), sponsor of the
meeting, said in a report that globalized markets and rapid
technological change will dictate further adjustments in the size
and skills of the workforce in the industry -- an engine and
indicator of economic growth in nearly all parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Per capita consumption of steel, mainly in the form of
construction and of durable goods, is closely linked to the level
and rate of a country's economic development, said the ILO
report. The annual per capita consumption ranges from an average
of 17 kilograms in Africa to 625 kilograms in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, consumption in industrialized countries is expected
to remain static or even decrease slightly in the coming decade,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Strong growth is, however, expected in Asia (40 percent over
the period), notably in China (150 percent) and, to a lesser
extent, in Latin America (18 percent)", the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministerial Meeting on Poverty Held in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The inaugural meeting of
ASEAN Ministers on Rural Development and Poverty Eradication ended
in Malaysia today with a firm commitment to eradicating poverty in
the region.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the one-day meeting held in Subang Jaya near here
today, the ministers from the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) member countries signed a "Ministerial
Understanding" on ASEAN cooperation in rural development and
poverty eradication.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are "firmly committed toward realizing the vision
of eradicating poverty, with particular emphasis on promoting the
development of progressive, prosperous, and self-reliant rural
communities, and thus contributing toward creating a caring
society in the ASEAN member countries," the document said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers "unanimously approved" the framework for the
ASEAN Plan of Action on rural development and poverty eradication,
which will address the challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The challenges include socio-economic disparity, unemployment
and underemployment, low productivity, illiteracy, backwardness,
inadequate economic opportunities, social problems, lack of basic
infrastructure and social amenities, environmental degradation and
the impact of globalization and information technology in the
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the objectives of the action plan, the ministers
outlined a number of strategic thrusts including developing human
resources and capacity for policy formulation, promoting
experience sharing, encouraging participation of the private
sector, promoting collaboration with ASEAN governmental
organizations and building common positions on matters related to
rural development and poverty eradication.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen and coordinate ASEAN collaboration, the ministers
agreed to meet at least once in two years with informal meetings
in between, but ASEAN senior officials will meet on the subject at
least once a year.
</P>
<P>
The ministers decided that their next informal meeting will be
held in late 1998 in Indonesia and their formal meeting will take
place in 1999 in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
All nine ASEAN members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam -- were
represented at the meeting.  
</P>
