<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> C'wealth Membership Optional, Says Abacha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General Sani
Abacha has described the Commonwealth as a voluntary association of
independent.
</P>
<P>
He said sovereign nations with member states free to exercise
their right to join or leave if so desired, the daily Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Abacha made the remarks in the capital Abuja on Wednesday as the
Commonwealth turned down Nigeria's request to be represented at the
group's heads of government meeting to be open tomorrow in Edinburgh,
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
On his return to Abuja after a state visit to Ghana and the Gambia,
Abacha said no nation could be compelled to join or leave the
organization.
</P>
<P>
"There is no compulsion. it is free and any member can be there and
any member can opt out," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So I think the main aspect of the Commonwealth is to focus on the
socio-economic relevance of member states. I doubt if the Commonwealth
is there to massage or satisfy the ego or sentiment or the historical
perspective of some powers that used to be in the past. We have passed
that stage," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Secretary-General, Chief Emeka Anyaoku, refused on
Wednesday the appeal of Nigeria to be at the Edinburgh summit to defend
itself, which is expected to decide on the country's membership.
</P>
<P>
The refusal came on the heels of the British government's resolve
to prevent Nigeria's representatives from participating in
the deliberations in which a final decision on Nigeria, which was
suspended from the body in 1995, is expected to be taken.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Nigeria's Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi in a letter to
Anyaoku sought permission to attend the summit so as to state the
country's case for re-entry.
</P>
<P>
But the British Foreign Office argued on Wednesday that Nigeria
should not take part in any Commonwealth meeting while the suspension
subsisted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Continue to Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's stock market fell
today for the fourth day this week, dropping by 1,211.47 points to
close at 10,426.30.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index, the key indicator of Hong Kong's blue
chips, broke through the 10,000-point level in morning trading to
9,998.07, down 1,639.7 points, before recovering a little in
afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
The morning plunge was the biggest drop in points in the
market's history and the largest percentage fall since October 26,
1987, when the market plummeted 1,120.7 points to close at
2,241.69, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index closed at 11,637,
down 765 points, the lowest finish since April this year. The
index had already lost 630 and 567 points respectively Monday and
Tuesday following sharp falls on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
However, today's market turnover amounted to 34,031 million HK
dollars (about 4,374 million U.S. dollars), up from Wednesday's
23,561 million HK dollars (about 3,028 million U.S. dollars),
Tuesday's 19,260 million HK dollars (2,470 million U.S. dollars)
and Monday's 17,260 million HK dollars (2,210 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Today's stock market drop followed three days of steep falls,
with investors gripped by panic selling on fears of higher
interest rates and currency instability.
</P>
<P>
The market has been further weakened mainly by selling
pressures from overseas and domestic funds managers and by renewed
 currency volatility in the Asia-Pacific region, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
There are also reports that the main reason for today's fall
appeared to be a huge rise in short-term interbank rates here.
Banks here announced earlier today that their prime rate would
rise by 0.75 percentage points to 9.5 percent from Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong banking authorities made no statement, but the
hike appeared designed to head off borrowing for speculative
attacks on the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong dollar is the only Asian currency still pegged to
the U.S. dollar. Several other Asian currencies have plunged since
July in a wave of turmoil sweeping markets from Indonesia and
Malaysia to Singapore and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the tumbling stock market, Financial Secretary of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Donald Tsang
reiterated his determination this morning to defend the Hong Kong
dollar, noting that the SAR's economy remains stable.
</P>
<P>
"I am not worried at all, because it is a market. A market, of
course, depends on the sentiments," he said. The SAR has 80-odd
billion U.S. dollars of foreign exchange reserves, without any
debt.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it is a matter for people to panic about, but I
believe very strongly in defending our dollars," Tsang said. "Our
dollars reflect the fundamentals of Hong Kong and the fundamentals
are exceedingly robust."
</P>
<P>
He is of the view that Hong Kong's companies are still making
good profits and they are turning in good dividends for the
shareholders. "It is very sound investment generally," he pointed
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
