<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6,750 People Killed in Road Accidents in Seven </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Over 6,750 people have
been killed in 34,837 road accidents in Mozambique since 1990,
and 37,481 people wounded, local newspaper Noticias reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a recent report from the National Institute
of Vehicles as saying that the actual death tolls far exceeds the
number given, for some injured people died later without the
Knowledge of the police.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that the capital city of Maputo has the
highest accident rate of the whole country, which stands at 49.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, due to low speed driving, quick rescue and better
medical condition, the death rate in Maputo is relatively low.
The city witnessed the death of 1,176 people in 12,695 road
accidents since 1991, in which 10,600 people were injured.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes the traffic accidents to out-of-date
road condition and signal system which in turn leads to rapid
damage to vehicles, as well as speeding, drunk driver and
violation of traffic rules.
</P>
<P>
About 23 percent of accidents in Mozambique were caused by
drunk drivers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
