<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Fires in Indonesia Cause Huge Economic Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The total loss caused by forest
fires in Indonesia from April to September this year has reached
11,751 trillion rupiah (about 3.15 billion U.S. dollars), the
Indonesian Forum for Environment (WALHI) estimated.
</P>
<P>
According to the investigation results issued by the forum
Wednesday, 1,714 million hectares of forests have been damaged by
the fires in the period.
</P>
<P>
The smog and haze caused by the fires also affected the health
of many people in the country as well as in neighboring countries
like Malaysia and Singapore. By October 20, it said, as many as 23
people had died because of the haze and approximately 30,000
people had been suffering from respiratory illnesses and eye
irritations.
</P>
<P>
The haze also caused the cancellation of many flights and
collision of boats in the country. The Garuda Airbus a-300 crash
near Medan, capital of North Sumatra, on September 26, which
killed all 234 people on board, was possibly caused by the thick
haze, WALHI added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the local press reported today that just when people
thought it was safe to return to the streets unmasked, thick haze
from brush and forest fires made a return to several towns in
Sumatra and Kalimantan islands, forcing the closure of at least
eight airports on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted the Environmental Impact Management Agency
as saying the number of hot spots, or fire locations, had
increased from 36 to 54 on the previous day.
</P>
<P>
Intensive international assistance has helped reduce the impact
of the fires in Indonesia in the past two months and as of last
week the situation was believed to be under control.
</P>
<P>
But intermittent rain has worsened the situation as it produced
more smoke instead of extinguishing the fires.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
