<HEADLINE> ILO Calls Consensus on Core Labor Norms a Must </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) has underlined the need for a broad consensus
on core labor standards in the international multilateral system
and called India a key player in realizing it.
</P>
<P>
in a interview with the Press Trust of India here today, ILO
Deputy Director-General Kari Tapiola said, "India is one of the
countries without which we cannot have a broad consensus on core
labor standards."
</P>
<P>
Tapiola held talks with Indian Labor Ministry officials and
representatives of workers' organizations in the past two days and
is to discuss today with employers organizations the question of
core labor standards and what ILO can do to improve the observance
of these standards and review the ILO program on the abolition of
child labor in India.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian government and social partners have a
positive view and are supporting ILO actions on key labor
standards and all of them reject a link between labor standards
and trade.
</P>
<P>
The ILO is expected to meet in November this year and discuss
ways to intensify implementation and improve the follow-up
mechanism for the promotion of the core labor principles in member
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
