<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Kia Group to Be Disbanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 23 (Xinhua) -- South Korean government has decided
to place the financially ailing Kia Group's two auto-making flagships
- Kia Motors Co. and Asia Motors Co. - under court receivership to
solve the dragging Kia Group crisis.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Kia Group, the eighth largest conglomerate and the
second largest car-maker in South Korea, with 28 subsidiaries, will be
inevitably disbanded.
</P>
<P>
Creditor banks said Thursday that they will file an application
within this week at the earliest for court receivership of the two
units.
</P>
<P>
The decision made by government is to end the prolonged Kia crisis
aimed to calm the escalating financial unrest under the market
economic frame, said economic observers.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision announced by Deputy Prime Minister for
Finance and Economy Kang Kyong-shik Wednesday, Kia Motors will be
operated as a state-run public company until its management is
normalized and its future will be decided by the next administration.
</P>
<P>
The loans by Korea Development Bank (KDB) to Kia Motors will be
converted into the state-run bank's investment capital, making KDB the
motor company's biggest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government has decided to hand over Asia
Motors to a third party in the near future, on the condition that its
commercial vehicle production lines in Kwangju are not relocated.
</P>
<P>
The government also calls for the resignation of most of the
current management and will appoint asset trustees within the
companies under negotiations with the court.
</P>
<P>
Both commercial banks and merchant banks reacted positively to
the government action, saying it would help stabilize the domestic
financial market.
</P>
<P>
Kia owed domestic financial institutions 9.43 trillion won
(about 14 billion U.S. dollars) as of the end of May this year,
including 5.38 trillion won (6 billion dollars) to commercial
banks and 4.5 trillion won (5 billion dollars) to merchant banks
and brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the long-awaited government decision, the local bourse
sharply rebounded to mark a daily jump. Meanwhile, the South Korean
currency also showed signs of recovery. Domestic stock prices and the
South Korean won have both experienced sharp declines in recent days,
mainly because of the prolonged Kia issue.
</P>
<P>
While financial circles responded positively to the government's
decision, it prompted an immediate strike by 20,000 Kia workers.
</P>
<P>
The Kia Group opposed the government's decision, saying that it
will mobilize all legal measures available to deter the court
receivership, stead seeking for court protection to grasp their
current management right. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Welcomes Overseas Investment in Farming, Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Tibet Autonomous Region has
enormous agricultural development potential and resources, said
Tibet's representative to an exposition here, but foreign
investment is badly needed.
</P>
<P>
Ma Guanghui, an official from the Regional Department of
Agriculture and Animal Husbandry who leads Tibet's delegation,
made the remarks today at the Third China Agricultural Exposition
under way in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said so far there is no overseas investment in agricultural
development except for a few international donors to carry out
several integrated development projects.
</P>
<P>
Tibet covers more than 1.2 million square kilometers, Ma
said. The region's location on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau and its
unique geological environment and climate has resulted in large
areas of grasslands, farmlands and forests, he said.
</P>
<P>
These resources are yet to be developed due to lack of funds,
Ma said, but in recent years many private investors from inland
provinces have invested in farming and husbandry projects in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investors, he said, the regional government
has formulated a series of preferential policies and listed a
number of projects.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that in 1996 Tibet produced 810,000
tons of grain, 116,000 tons of meat, 166,400 tons of dairy
products, 9,300 tons of wool and 1,500 tons of aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Tibet mainly exports wool to neighboring Nepal and
India, Ma said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
