<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Talks With Rebels to Continue: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the
Philippine government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) will go on despite the recent tension in the southern
Mindanao Island, Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat said today.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly press conference, Abat confirmed that he and
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, had
agreed to push through the peace talks during a meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abat said he had gained a pledge from the MILF leader that the
rebels would not hold any public executions of people they
themselves find guilty.
</P>
<P>
At present, negotiators from the government and the MILF are
holding another urgent meeting in Mindanao to discuss last week's
terrorist attack on a military camp in Mindanao and the execution
of two alleged criminals by the MILF early this month.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been high in central Mindanao after the military
built up its troops in areas surrounding a major rebels' camp in
retaliation for the terrorist attack and the MILF's execution of
the alleged criminals.
</P>
<P>
The MILF had threatened to scrap their peace talks with the
government if the military continued to increase troops near the
rebel stronghold.
</P>
<P>
But after an emergency meeting Tuesday, the two sides agreed to
respect a cease-fire signed in July and pull back their forces to
their previous positions. Tension has been easing up in central
Mindanao following the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Abat also confirmed that the Army's Sixth Infantry Division has
begun to reposition its troops posted near the MILF camp.
</P>
<P>
With an estimated membership of 12,000, the MILF is currently
the largest anti-government force in the country. It began peace
negotiations with Manila early this year, but the talks have been
on-and-off due to sporadic fighting between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The larger Moro National Liberation Front signed a peace deal
with Manila last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
