<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Gates Defends Microsoft Against Monopoly Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Microsoft
Corporation Bill Gates today rejected the charges of monopoly
against his company by the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft did not violate a consent decree it signed in 1995
which barred it from imposing anticompetitive licensing terms on
personal computer makers, Gates told an audience of top technology
executives in Scottsdale, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department on Monday accused Microsoft of forcing
computer makers to include the Microsoft Internet browser in
pre-loaded software by using the monopoly on its Windows computer
operating system in violation of the 1995 decree.
</P>
<P>
The department asked a federal court in Washington to fine
Microsoft 1 million U.S. dollars a day if the alleged violations
continue.
</P>
<P>
The charges partly originated from complaints by small
companies about Microsoft's aggressive efforts to incorporate new
functions into its Windows operating system, whose '95 version are
installed on more than 80 percent of the PCs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Microsoft prohibited Compaq Computer Corp. and two
other major U.S computer makers from eliminating or limiting the
presence of its Internet Explorer Web browser on their products.
</P>
<P>
Ed Black, chairman of the Computer and Communications Industry
Association, said that any smart company does not want to be in a
monopolistic situation with just one supplier. It's in their
long-term interest to have more than one source so as to gain
negotiation power.
</P>
<P>
Gates said that the 1995 decree allows Microsoft to enhance
Windows over time and merging Internet function with the operating
system is a natural extension of the software.
</P>
<P>
It is Microsoft itself, but not a government lawyer, should be
able to decide what improvements can be made within its products
and how it may sell them, Gates noted.
</P>
<P>
An antitrust lawyer said that it is difficult to draw a line
between improving a product and monopolizing a market.
</P>
<P>
If the Washington-based U.S. District judge agrees that browser
and operating system should be separate, the Justice Department
could force Microsoft to unbundle the browser capability from
Windows 95, a step that would undermine Microsoft's long-range
strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
