<HEADLINE> Intra-COMESA Trade to Be Increased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The annual trade volume among
COMESA (Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa) countries
will be increased to six billion U.S. dollars from the current
2.4 billion dollars with the establishment of its Free Trade Area
(FTA)in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted COMESA Acting Director General
Erastus Mwencha as predicting that FTA will create immense
business opportunities for entrepreneurs within and from outside
the region.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha told a COMESA "yellow card" meeting last Thursday in a
written speech that free movement of goods and services within
the region will require banking, insurance and other financial
support services.
</P>
<P>
There are indications that cross-border investment in the
insurance industry is gathering pace as most member countries
through the COMESA monetary harmonization program have
liberalized the capital account, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said globalization of world economic activities
presents opportunities and challenges to the insurance industry
in the region which will see many insurance companies from
advanced countries set up business in COMESA countries.
</P>
<P>
He called for closer cooperation including joint ventures
among insurance companies in COMESA for the industry to be able
to meet the challenge of stiff competition to be posed by
entrants from overseas.
</P>
<P>
"The liberalization of financial services will enhance
competition and improve sectoral efficiency, leading to lower
costs, better quality and more choice of financial services,"
Mwencha noted.
</P>
<P>
The liberalization will induce governments to improve
micro-economic management, domestic policy interventions, in
credit markets and financial sector regulations and supervision,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
