<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Nigerian newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Daily Times
</P>
<P>
-- Nigeria's head of state General Sani Abacha Wednesday
described the commonwealth as an association of independent,
sovereign nations with member states free to exercise their right
to join or leave if so desired, just as the body's
secretary-general Emeka Anyaoku rejected the country's request to
be represented at its heads of state and government meeting
starting tomorrow in Edinburgh, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States ambassador-designate to Nigeria William
Twaddell assessed on Wednesday his prospective host country's
role in the community of nations and declared that "Nigeria is too
important to be ignored" but the U.S. stand on Nigeria will
remain.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian
</P>
<P>
-- The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
foreign ministers reopened talks with representatives of the
military junta in Sierra Leone on Wednesday in Conakry, Guinea on
the return of power to ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
-- Manufacturers in Nigeria have again expressed doubt over
the efficacy of various measures by the federal government to
revive the comatose economy of the country.
</P>
<P>
This Day
</P>
<P>
-- Shell Petroleum Development Company western division has
threatened to stop exploration and exploitation of oil in the
Niger Delta in south Nigeria, if the spate of attacks by youths in
the area on its facilities and personnel does not abate. 
</P>
