<HEADLINE> Legal Abortions Increase in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africans are having
abortions at the rate of about three women an hour, according to
a survey by the Reproductive Rights Alliance (RRA).
</P>
<P>
In the first six months since South Africa adopted Abortion
Law in February, nearly 13,000 legal terminations were performed,
said RRA.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in many hospitals are struggling to keep up with the
growing demand for abortion since the procedure was legalized in
February, medical department sources said.
</P>
<P>
The choice of the termination of pregnancy allows pregnancy
terminations for all women over 16 in the first 12 weeks in
certain cases.
</P>
<P>
In Gauteng Province where Pretoria, the administrative capital
and Johannesburg, a biggest trading center in south africa are
situated, 6,332 abortions performed from February to August
represent half of all requests, said RRA Administrator Judi
Merckel.
</P>
<P>
Those who are not able to get legal abortions continue to
support the illegal backstreet abortion industry which flurished
during apartheid era, she said.
</P>
<P>
Before abortions are legalized, up to 300,000 back
street abortions were performed each year. Of these, an estimated
43,000 of these women were hospitalized from medical
complications, RRA said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that women from neighboring Botswana,
Zimbabwe, Zambia and countries where abortion is either not
easily available or illegal have made the long journey to
have the procedure in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Merckel predicted that the legal abortion rate is expected to
increase further in the short term with improved medical access,
but will eventually subside as a result of greater awareness
through education programs provided at clinics and hospitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Efforts to Improve Ownership Structure (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By the end of 1996, China's state assets amounted to 6.58
trillion yuan, up 15.4 percent over the previous year, maintaining
a higher increase than the gross national product (GNP).
</P>
<P>
The country's gross domestic product (GDP) was 6.8 trillion
last year, to which the sector of the public ownership contributed
76 percent, accounting for 2.8 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector had a trillion yuan in taxes and profits
last year, 877.6 billion yuan of which was generated by
enterprises of the public ownership, accounting for 88 percent of
the total with the state-owned businesses contributing more than
600 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Economies of public or state ownership have been growing
steadily in the process of the ownership structure
readjustment. So there is no worry about the possibility of
"privatization", economists said.
</P>
<P>
A consensus has been reached that the proportion of the public
ownership in the national economy is no longer the final
target. Instead, the state sector should withdraw from the fields
in which it works less efficiently than other economies, and turns
to the life-blood areas for national economy such as energy,
power, transport and other infrastructure fields.
</P>
<P>
China is effectuating a strategic reorganization of state
enterprises by good management of large enterprise groups while
relaxing the control over small ones and invigorating them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Efforts to Improve Ownership Structure (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Accordingly, the state enterprises are encouraged to invest in
national defense industry, minting industry, aerospace, large
infrastructure projects, large resource-tapping programs, and the
high-tech projects that bear strategic importance on the country's
long-term development.
</P>
<P>
In principle, the state will no longer spend on non-strategic
areas while readjusting the layouts of national economy, and will
relax control over the areas in which collective or non-public
ownership economies can do better.
</P>
<P>
"The non-public sector is an important part of our socialist
market economy. We should continue to encourage and guide the
non-public sector comprising self-employed and private businesses
to facilitate its sound development," Jiang Zemin reiterated in
his report to the Congress.
</P>
<P>
Historical experience and practices by world market economies
have shown that the strategic reorganization of state economy
should rely on existing superior state-owned enterprises,
industrial policies and market systems, economists said.
</P>
<P>
An effort must be made to overcome the factors that greatly
hinder a sound operation of the capital market, with top priority
placed on clarifying the complicated relationships between state
enterprises and administration, and ownership of property, and
eliminating regional and sectional boundaries, economists urged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
