<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Pests Invade Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Larger grain borers (LGB),
a deadly grain pest, have invaded into eastern Uganda, a local
scientist warned Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Salim Nahdy, Director of Kawanda Agricultural Research
Institute, told The New Vision that the pest was found recently
in eastern Busia district.
</P>
<P>
The pest was detected first in February this year from a
consignment of maize, transported by the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) to Rwanda and the
Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Constant Bazirake, Acting Commissioner for plant protection in
the Ministry of Agriculture, Animal Industry and Fisheries,
blamed the recent pest invasion on the violation by ICRC on the
related regulation of Uganda, under which the food should be
opened only at its destination.
</P>
<P>
The pest poses a threat to stored maize, dry maize in the
field, sweet potatoes, rice, sorghum and wheat.
</P>
<P>
The pest had invaded Tanzania through food aid in late 1970s. It
spread to Kenya, Rwanda, Burundi and Democratic Republic of Congo
since then.
</P>
<P>
Illegal border grain trade can bring the pest into Uganda at
any time, he warned.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan scientists would introduce soon predator beetles of
teretriosoma nigrescens into the border districts of Busia and
Tororo as a preventive measure against the weevil, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicle Sales in Thailand Down in January-September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's total vehicle sales
during the first nine months of this year dropped by 25.9 percent
from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Only 322,000 vehicles were sold in the period, of which 117,000
were cars, 167,000 pickup trucks and 38,000 buses and heavy
trucks, according to a Toyota Motor (Thailand) report issued
today.
</P>
<P>
During the same period of last year, about 405,000 vehicles
were sold.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, sales of buses and trucks have suffered the
sharpest decrease, falling by 41 percent, followed by pickups with
a drop of 31.9 percent and cars 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Among the top 10 car sellers, only Toyota and Honda registered
increased sales, rising by 4.3 percent and 5.4 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The market for imported cars shrank considerably as a result of
the depreciating baht and higher luxury goods tax.
</P>
<P>
Sales of Volvo were down 34 percent, Volkswagen 26 percent, BMW
 18.5 percent and Mercedes-Benz 12.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
In September alone, total sales of vehicles of all categories
decreased by as much as 73 percent as a result of the weakening
purchasing power of consumers.
</P>
<P>
Last week the government lifted import duties on
completely-built-up cars to 80 percent from 42 percent and 68.5
percent to discourage luxury spending and increase government
revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
