<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Painting Duplicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A new copy of "Riverside
Scenes at the Qingming Festival," an ancient Chinese painting in
the Song Dynasty (960-1275), has been finished in northern China's
Hebei Province after four years of painstaking work.
</P>
<P>
The original painting by Zhang Zeduan, a famous ancient Chinese
painter, depicts the hustle and bustle of the eastern suburbs of
the Song capital of Bianliang, which has now been renamed Kaifeng in
Henan Province. It is now kept in the Palace Museum.
</P>
<P>
The new copy, using ancient duplicating skills and modern
printing technology, was completed by Wang Kairu, an expert in
Tangshan.
</P>
<P>
The copy imitates the painting patterns, colors and shades, and
the hundreds of cuts and stains in the original. Yang Xin, head of
the Palace Museum, praised the quality of the copy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Step Toward Blocking of Yangtze Mainstream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The planned blocking of the
Yangtze mainstream has achieved new breakthrough last night, with
the opening in the coffer dams narrowed down to 130 meters ahead
of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The further narrowing paved the way for the final damming of
the Yangtze mainstream, since it increased the water speed in the
diversion canal and the movement of silt, according to a water
conservation expert with the Three Gorges Project Development
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
For the first time the water flow in the diversion channel
bypassed the main river channel on October 22. Water surged
through the diversion channel at a rate of 5,710 cu.m. per second,
or 820 cu.m. per second more than in the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President with the corporation Wang Jiazhu said the
opening in the coffer dams will be further narrowed down to 40 to
50 meters on November 5, as a final preparation for the daming of
the Yangtze river on November 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
