<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Goes Ahead With Forestry Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenya plans to launch the
third phase of a forestry model development project next month
which will focus its researches on variety of trees, "Kenya
Times" report today.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed here Wednesday between the Kenyan
and Japanese governments, the project will run until the year of
2003.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Wamatu Njoroge, Permanent Secretary
for the Ministry of Research, Technical Training and Technology,
said that the third phase of the project will dwell more on tree
species. Apart from indegenous trees, he said, others which are
considered of importance to the local people are those which
provide timber, fuel and food.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official pointed out that his ministry is in charge
of research into the different species of trees during the
project while implementation of the findings will be carried out
by the Environment and Natural Resources Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the project is to be also concluded next
month with an mount of 6 million U.S. Dollars spent during the
phase.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Minoru Tagami, resident representative
of the Japan International Cooperation Agency, said that his
government would provide about 13 million Dollars for the third
phase of the project which has been in effect for the last 10
years.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the project is aimed at creating a
relationship between mankind and forests using technologies
developed over the years.
</P>
<P>
The project came about as a result of study which showed
excessive felling of trees to produce firewood and charcoal in
the East African country, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
