<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Expresses Satisfaction over Sino-Cape Verde Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
has voiced his satisfaction over the ever-closing relationship
between China and Cape Verde, pledging to expand bilateral
cooperation in politics, economy and international issues.
</P>
<P>
China attaches great importance to its relationship with Cape
Verde, Jiang told visiting Cape Verde Prime Minister Carlos Veiga
during their meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
As the 21st century approaches, the healthy, solid and
all-round cooperative ties between the two countries will enter
into a new development era, Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of diplomatic relations in 1976, he
said, bilateral cooperation in different fields have produced
considerable results, while the two countries sympathized with and
supported each other in world issues.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also expressed his thanks and appreciation over Veiga and
the Cape Verde government for the "One China" policy and
not conducting any official contacts with the Taiwan
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Jiang described the talks between Veiga and Premier Li Peng on
Wednesday as candid, cordial and productive and expressing the
conviction that Veiga's visit will help deepen mutual
understanding and friendship and further improve cooperative ties.
</P>
<P>
The president spoke highly of Cape Verde's achievements in
safeguarding national stability and advancing economic
progress. China respects the political system and development road
chose by the Cape Verde government and people based on their own
national conditions, he added.
</P>
<P>
Veiga congratulated China on the successful convening of the
15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party, Hong Kong's
smooth return to the motherland, and China's great achievements in
its reform and opening up.
</P>
<P>
Cape Verde will always be China's solid and reliable friend,
Veiga said, adding that his government appreciates and supports
the important principles governing the development of Sino-African
relations expounded by President Jiang during his African tour in
May 1996.
</P>
<P>
Cape Verde is ready to establish a kind of strategic
partnership with China, and is full of confidence about the
further strengthening of their long-term, stable cooperation, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang asked Veiga to convey his kind regards to President
Antonio Monteiro, and Veiga in return conveyed President
Monteiro's regards to Jiang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
