<HEADLINE> Growth In East China Development Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The port city of Ningbo in east
China's Zhejiang province has had rapid development in its energy,
raw material processing, and export business.
</P>
<P>
The 29.6-sq.km. zone, which was approved in 1984, will become a
large transfer point, an important trader and energy and raw
material base, and large export zone.
</P>
<P>
The zone had spent 12.85 billion yuan (about 16 billion US
dollars) on fixed assets and 6.2 billion yuan on infrastructure by
the end of August this year. In January-August, industrial output
was up 30 percent and exports, 26.3 percent, over the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Investors from the United States, Japan, Singapore, Hongkong,
Taiwan, and elsewhere have established 420 joint ventures with a
combined contractual investment of 3.75 billion U.S. dollars, and
of which 869 million U.S. dollars have been actually used.
</P>
<P>
Some large multinational, like the Concord Group of the US,
Japan's Mitsui, and Korea's Samsung have set up in the zone, which
is developing light industry, building materials, textiles, food
processing, and shipbuilding, and improving pillar industries like
petrochemicals, iron and steel, and papermaking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
