<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harare's Centenary Celebrations Kick-off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Harare's official centenary
celebrations kicked off last night with the switching on of
lights in the city's first street Mall by Mayor Solomon Tawengwa.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was witnessed by scores of residents who gathered
at the intersection of the Mall and George Silundika Avenue.
</P>
<P>
A band played "Happy Birthday To You," marking Harare's first
100 years as a municipality as the mayor switched on the lights
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The mayor said there is nothing political about the occasion,
except that the residents are marking history for the sake of
their children. They are also marking the beginning of the next
100 years for the city as a municipality.
</P>
<P>
The full celebration program is expected to start from
November 6 and will run through November 10, when a lot of
activities including cultural exhibitions are lined up.
</P>
<P>
Harare graduated from being a sanitary board on October 22,
1897.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation of municipal status meant that the council
could now set bylaws, levy rates, raise loans and enter into
contracts.
</P>
<P>
It could also own land as opposed to the lower local
authorities who had to acquire land for developmental purposes
through the government.
</P>
<P>
Tawengwa said, "Harare is now the proud multi-racial
metropolis that all the residents have a reason to celebrate,
reminiscing on both our past glorious moments, and frustrating
moments, with the view to using this vital information to chart
the way forward."
</P>
<P>
He called on the people of Harare to make a decision on what
kind of city they look forward to in the next 100 years and
what form of legacy they want to leave behind for
posterity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
