<HEADLINE> Zhang Yimou's New Film Big Hit in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- "Keep Cool," a new film by
well-known Chinese film director Zhang Yimou, was a big hit in
Beijing cinema. Within a few days, the box-office revenue topped three
million yuan (about 361,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total box-office earnings of "Keep Cool" is expected to
exceed five million yuan, about half the average gross for foreign
films. The success of "Keep Cool" represents a trend for Chinese
movies to appeal to a mass market, said Gao Jun, an executive of
the Beijing Xingyinlian Movie Studios.
</P>
<P>
"Keep Cool" is the first movie about modern urban life by
Zhang, the director of "Red Sorghum" and "Qiuju Goes to
Court". Most of Zhang's previous films were set in the
countryside, Gao said, which is a change for audiences.
</P>
<P>
The participation of well-known Chinese actors such as Jiang
Wen, who also directed "In the Heat of the Sun," and Li Baotian,
who co-starred with Gong Li in "Ju Dou," ensured the movie's
popular appeal. Actress Qu Ying, a former model, succeeded Gong Li
as Zhang's female lead.
</P>
<P>
Audience members surveyed said that they liked the film because
of its relaxed pace and artistic taste.
</P>
<P>
Xingyinlian studios, producer of the movie, has heavily
promoted and advertised the film.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has experienced a booming movie market in recent
years. Box-office earnings for 76 of Beijing's cinemas exceeded
100 million yuan last year, with estimates of 110 million yuan for
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
