<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Draft Constitution to Go to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Justice Minister G.
L. Peiris said today that he was authorized by the Parliamentary
Select Committee to submit the new draft constitution to the
parliament on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He told a weekly news conference that the move marked the end
of the first phase of work on the charter, which had taken two and
a half years for political parties and the public to discuss.
</P>
<P>
The draft contains proposals for the establishment of a Union
of Regions with more autonomy given to local authorities in view
of ending the country's ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who is also in charge of constitutional affairs,
ethnic affairs and national integration, said, "The government is
firmly committed to implementing the constitutional reforms."
</P>
<P>
War is not the final solution to the conflict going on in Sri
Lanka between the majority Sinhalese people and the minority Tamil
people, he added.
</P>
<P>
The new draft constitution is a major peace initiative of the
current government, which stresses the need for reconciliation,
good governance, peace and ethnic harmony.
</P>
<P>
The 14-year-long conflict in Sri Lanka has claimed 55,000 lives
and rendered many people homeless.  
</P>
</TEXT>
