<HEADLINE> 300,000 Ugandans Suffer Epilepsy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- 300,000 Ugandans have epilepsy
but are not treated, the local newspaper The Crusader reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Helne Meinld, an epilepsy researcher from Danish Epilepsy
Association was quoted as saying that the association is ready to
treat Ugandan epileptics and to give material support to their
families.
</P>
<P>
Epilepsy is common in developing countries because of the lack
of treatment and parental care during child-giving and
child-rearing, Meinld said.
</P>
<P>
She urged parents and teachers not to fear epileptics (people
with epilepsy) and instead advised them to nurse and give proper
medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
The researcher criticised Ugandans who prefer traditional
herbs which is not a proper treatment for epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
She told the paper that her association counsels epileptics
and seeks help for them from the government.
</P>
<P>
Epilepsy is a medical condition in the brain that can suddenly
make one become unconscious or unable to control his/her
movements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
