<HEADLINE> China Suspends Urea Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Because chemical fertilizer
imports are out of control, China has decided to suspend imports
of urea, People's Daily (Overseas Edition) has reported.
</P>
<P>
China imported 9.3 million tons of urea in 1996, 1.6 million
tons more than needed. In addition, the country imported another
2.6 million tons of urea in the January-June period this year.
</P>
<P>
The excessive imports are affecting the country's domestic
market. Recently, 11 large nitrogenous fertilizer producers
appealed for protection of the state's large chemical fertilizer
producers.
</P>
<P>
China is the largest urea importer in the world, and the world
price for urea has dropped a lot because of China's reduction in
the amount of imported urea this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
