<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Helps 3 million Handicapped out of Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Liu Desheng, a handicapped
peasant in northeastern China's Liaoning Province, expects to make
9,000 yuan (about 1,084 U.S dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Just last year Liu, who was unable to work, lived in poverty
with his family of three on less than 1,000 yuan a year.
</P>
<P>
Liu's life changed after the government of Dengta City, where
he lives, loaned him 350 ducklings from a poverty-relief center
for the handicapped and gave him one ton of corn.
</P>
<P>
In recent years China has helped 3 million handicapped people
escape poverty by setting up a special "recovery and relief" loan
fund and poverty-relief centers for the handicapped, according to
Deng Pufang, chairman of the China Federation for the Disabled.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen million handicapped people live in poverty in
China. Adding family members of the disabled, the number accounts
for half of the nation's impoverished, including 2.7 million
living in extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
To help the handicapped out of poverty, the State Council set
up the "Recovery and Relief" Fund in 1992. The fund has granted
loans of 500 million yuan in the past two years alone and has
brought prosperity to 800,000 disabled persons in the first half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Many poverty-relief centers, which receive loans with favorable
terms from the government, have been set up to help the disabled.
</P>
<P>
One of the bases in Dengta, a poultry center, hatches 400,000
chickens and ducklings a year. The center has loaned thousands of
chickens and ducklings to 48 poor families with disabilities and
helped them gain an average annual income of 8,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local cadres in Dengta have volunteered to help disabled
persons individually, donating 1.18 million yuan to 509 families
and helping them solve specific practical problems.
</P>
<P>
China plans to meet the disabled persons' needs in food and
clothing by the end of this century, Deng said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
