<HEADLINE> Pressure Mounts for Price Rises: Thai Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The falling value of the baht
will increase pressure for price rises of consumer goods in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The declining value of the baht, which has plunged by 48.3
percent against the U.S. dollar since July 2, has further added to
the cost of production and made it very difficult for the Commerce
Ministry to control consumer goods prices, Commerce Minister
Narongchai Akrasanee was quoted as saying on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry maintains that only those consumer goods which are
seriously affected will be permitted to increase their prices
while those which are only slightly affected are requested to
maintain their prices for the benefit of the public, said Internal
Trade Department Director-General Suchai Jaovisidth, according to
a Bangkok Post report today.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier this month that the ministry had
approved price rises for more than 4,000 kinds of consumer goods,
with an increase range varying from a few percent to over 20
percent.  
</P>
