<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "White Pollution" Banned in Southwestern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, a newly designated
municipality in southwestern China, will forbid the production,
sale and use of food containers made of plastic foam effective
July 1, 1998, according to a government meeting held here recently.
</P>
<P>
Food containers made of plastic foam are condemned as "White
Pollution" because they do not decompose naturally and are
difficult to retrieve and dispose.
</P>
<P>
Local bureau of environmental protection statistics show that
200,000 fast-food containers were thrown away daily in Chongqing
in 1996. This white garbage, scattered along the railways or
floating along the Yangtze and Jialing rivers, has long irked
local residents.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulation, enterprises producing food
containers made of plastic foam should shift to recyclable
plastics, plant fiber or biologically soluble materials.
</P>
<P>
Sources say the 200,000 fast-food containers needed daily in
Chongqing will be fulfilled by enterprises already producing food
containers and cases that meet environmental standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilians to Make Space Trips in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 22 (Xinhua) -- An American private
aerospace company is taking reservations for trips on a
rocket-powered cruiser that would send civilian passengers 62
miles (99.8 kilometers) above the earth.
</P>
<P>
The voyages would start in 2001 and each cruiser would send 6
passengers per trip above the ozonosphere, where the sky turns
black and passengers would experience weightlessness for about two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
The Seattle-based company -- Zegrahm Space Voyages -- said at
least 15 people have made such reservations and each has put down
5,000 U.S. dollars on the 98,000 dollar trip.
</P>
<P>
Testing of the rocket engine is underway and manufacturing of
two cruisers is to start next year, said Scott Fitzsimmons, vice
president of the company, adding that the cruisers would look like
small jets but powered by rockets.
</P>
<P>
He said the flight itself will take no more than three hours
and passengers are required to spend five days at a space
institute, learning some basic knowledge about space voyage before
boarding on a cruiser. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Resets Dates for Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda electoral
commission decided to postpone the country's local government
elections which had been scheduled for November 1, local daily
The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Elections of village executive committees have been
rescheduled for November 6 and parish committee polls are now
slated for November 13.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement made on October 16 by the
electoral commission, elections of village and parish executive
committees are to be held on first of November and 8th of
November respectively.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the postponement is complaints from the Seventh
Day Adventist Church. The adventists, whose Sabbath is Saturday
(November 1,), petitioned the electoral commission to have the
polling days changed.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Resistance Movement system in
Uganda, the country has five levels of local governments under
the central government, namely from district councils down to
county councils, sub-county councils, parish councils and
village councils.
</P>
<P>
Uganda held its first direct presidential election in May 1996
while parliamentary elections were held in June of the year.
</P>
<P>
In November 1996, the Ugandan central government announced
that local government elections are to be held between March and
April 1997, but were postponed several times due to the lack of
election funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
