<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "El Nino" Causes Heavy Rains in Kenya's Coastal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The torrential rains pounding
coastal area in Kenya during the past five days are due to the El
Nino phenomenon, the Daily Nation today quoted a weatherman as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from Kenya's Meteorological Department (MD) show
that the port city of Mombasa has in the past 20 days received
761 mm of rainfall while its usual October average is 97 mm.
</P>
<P>
The amount received in the past 20 days is about 75 percent of
the total annual rainfall for the coastal town, according to MD
of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Njoroge, MD Deputy Director, said the El Nino episode
is expected to worsen next month, predicting that the coastal
area of the country would receive heavier rains in the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
A similar rainfall trend is picking up in Western and Nyanza
provinces, west Kenya, the weatherman added.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the El Nino which started in March/April
would reach maturity in December with most rains falling in
November in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino phenomenon is the result of abnormal rises in sea
surface temperatures in the Pacific region, leading to extreme
worldwide climatic conditions such as cyclones, floods and
droughts.
</P>
<P>
Its effects were last registered in Kenya in the 1984
drought. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
