<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's River Water Diversion Project Going Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Yan-Huang-Ding Yellow
River Water Diversion Project, which started in China in 1988, has
begun to benefit local poor people.
</P>
<P>
Its purpose is to improve the life and production of farmers in
Yanchi and Tongxing counties in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region,
Huanxian county in Gansu Province, and Dingbian county in Shaanxi
Province, all in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The project was also designed to provide drinking water for
360,000 people and 1.27 million head of livestock, and to develop
more than 20,000 ha of irrigated farmland.
</P>
<P>
Twenty thousand people have been resettled in the project area,
and 5,460 ha of land improved.
</P>
<P>
The major part of the project was completed last year in
Ningxia, where 11 pumping stations, a 100-km canal, and related
infrastructure are doing well.
</P>
<P>
Yanchi county has developed 4,000 ha of farmland and 600 ha of
shelterbelts and economic forests. And nearly 10,000 farmers have
settled in the project area and are provided with clean
water. They produced more than 10 million kg of grain in the past
few years and earn 1,000 yuan per capita.  
</P>
</TEXT>
