<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Chinese Farmers Take Lead in Using Science, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The better educated of the
young Chinese farmers are using science and and technology to make
more money.
</P>
<P>
Yu Changjun, of Shuangjingzi village in northwest China's
Liaoning province, is one example of this new breed and has come
to be known as the "king of shrimps" in the province because he
earned a million yuan (about 120,000 US dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Yu began raising shrimps in the early 1980s, but suffered a
loss because he didn't understand the business, and by 1990, his
losses had risen to 260,000 yuan on a 70-ha water plot.
</P>
<P>
So he turned to universities and research institutes for help,
and even went down to visit a shrimp farm in Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
His first results came in 1995, when his shrimp harvest brought
him 800,000 yuan in profits. This year he expects a better yield.
</P>
<P>
The province has three million young people in rural areas, and
many of them have made a name in different forms of agriculture,
and recently, 100 were selected as role models.
</P>
<P>
The shift has come in relying more on science and technology in
their farm work, instead of past experience as their fathers did.
</P>
</TEXT>
