<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Declining Illiterate Rate in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The literacy rate has improved
dramatically in the Tibet Autonomous Region, rising from 5 percent
in the 1950s to 60 percent in 1997. The literacy gains have been
attributed to education systems developed in the Tibetan language.
</P>
<P>
About 330,000 students are studying at more than 4,000 schools
in Tibet covering elementary and secondary grades, professional
training and adult education.
</P>
<P>
The number of pupils in elementary schools increased to 284,000
in 1997 from 157,000 in 1990, up 26.5 percent, while in high
schools, the number increased from 26,000 to 40,000 in the same
time span, according to an official from the local Education
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Professional education and adult education for young people
also are developing quickly. Professional education centers have
been established in five cities and prefectures along with
short-term training centers in counties and villages to teach
practical skills. These centers play an important role in
increasing the literacy rate among young people, from 37 percent
in 1990 to 46 percent today.
</P>
<P>
The number of teachers, mainly Tibetan, also has increased from
10,000 six years ago to 17,000 in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracking Down on Economic Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 169,700 cases of such
crimes as counterfeiting, profiteering and smuggling have been
opened in the first six months of 1997. Of those, 9,580 cases
already have been resolved in the legal system, the State
Administration for Industry and Commerce (SAIC) has announced.
</P>
<P>
Of the cases under investigation, 7,363 are categorized as
"serious" or "most serious" because they involve 10,000 yuan
(about 1,200 U.S. dollars) or more. The combined value of these
cases topped 3.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown by category of some of the economic crimes includes:
</P>
<P>
-- 4,733 cases involving unfair competition, 4.93 percent of
the total;
</P>
<P>
-- 11,700 cases of suspected consumer fraud, 12.21 percent;
</P>
<P>
-- 22,291 cases of profiteering, 23.26 percent;
</P>
<P>
-- More than 30,500 cases of counterfeiting or shoddy goods,
31.86 percent; and
</P>
<P>
-- 3,402 cases of smuggling, 3.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the crimes, SAIC officials said counterfeiting and
shoddy goods appropriating brand-name products are among the most
troublesome economic crimes. The value of such cases has risen
dramatically with 439 cases involving 100,000 yuan to one million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Also on the rise is consumer fraud, increasing by 156.64
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
