<HEADLINE> Japanese Women Living in DPRK Ready to Visit Hometown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of Japanese
women, who have been living in Korea for nearly 35 years, is
preparing to visit to their homeland, a spokesman for the
Asia-Pacific Peace Committee (APPC)in the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I hope they make the visit as planned," The spokesman
said. "This can be a chance to resolve unsettled humanitarian
questions existing between Korea and Japan and boost the close and
friendly relations between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said they are aware of the preparations
undertaken in Japan thanks to the concern of the Japanese
government and Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Last July, an APPC spokesman stated that the committee will do
everything necessary to see that the senior Japanese women visit
their Homeland.
</P>
<P>
Government and Red Cross officials from the two countries also
held talks in Beijing and reached an agreement on the visit
recently.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese women living in Korea are from two separate
groups: some came to Korea and married Korean men during World War
II while the country was occupied by Japan; the others married
Korean husbands in Japan and later moved to Korea. They are all
senior citizens now and very anxious to visit their homeland.
</P>
</TEXT>
