<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Urged to Pay More Attention to AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS epidemic that is
sweeping Asia is especially worrying for Bangladesh because of its
location and other health factors, the independent United News of
Bangladesh (UNB) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has 83 reported cases of HIV, the virus that causes
the fatal AIDS, and ten of them developed full-blown AIDS and six
have died, UNB said.
</P>
<P>
"These figures in Bangladesh are a gross underestimation," Dr.
Lisa Messersmith, Country Program Adviser of the UNAIDS told a
meeting in Dhaka recently.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, she said, is at risk because of many poor health
factors such as sexually transmitted diseases, especially among
urban poor, low use of condoms, minimum screening of blood and
increase in injectable drug.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has remained out of limelight (in cases of AIDS) not
because the number of infected persons is few, but because the
number of victims is not known, UNB quoted David Lockwood, UN
Resident Coordinator in Bangladesh, as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the rapid spread of the disease in neighboring India
and Myanmar should be especially worrying for Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
According to Messersmith, at least 8,500 people get infected
with HIV -- 1,000 of them children -- worldwide every day.
</P>
<P>
She warned that at least four million cases will be detected
every year in Asia alone in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Both the UN officials called for greater awareness about the
danger of AIDS in Bangladesh, the UNB said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
