<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment in Chinese City Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIANYUNGANG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investment has
increased in foreign-funded agricultural enterprises in
Lianyungang, a port city in eastern China's Jiangsu Province, in
the last five years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the city government has approved a contracted
overseas investment of over 100 million US dollars for enterprises
developing agricultural resources and processing farm produce. Of
the investment, more than 50 million have been used.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 100 overseas-funded agricultural enterprises,
of which, 45 have an annual export valume of more than five
million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of export-oriented farming is due to the
city's rich natural resources and favorable investment
environment, said Mayor Xia Geng.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural industrialization is the key to developing the
city's rural economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
To compete in the international market, the city has formulated
preferential policies to attract more overseas investors, Xia
said.
</P>
<P>
The city's exports topped 1.6 billion yuan (200 million
U.S. dollars) in 1996, accounting for 70 percent of its total
export volume. And, its exports of vegetables, edible seaweed and
feed ranked first in the country.
</P>
<P>
The city has brought 40,000 hectares of land for vegetable
production, 13,000 hectares for fruit growing, 8,000 hectares for
prawns breeding, and 2,700 hectares for seaweed
cultivation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
