<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Infrastructure Crisis Looming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has warned India of a grave infrastructure crisis, local
newspaper Business Standard said here today.
</P>
<P>
The bank has also pointed out that the Indian government's
public sector disinvestment policy is flawed and lacks clarity.
</P>
<P>
In its forthcoming report on India, a draft copy of which has
been sent to the Indian Finance Ministry, the ADB said, "India's
infrastructural problems have been made significantly worse by the
continued decline in public sector expenditure, both for operation
and maintenance, new investment and the limited progress in
attracting private sector funding into key infrastructure
sectors."
</P>
<P>
The report has noted the fiscal correction package announced by
the government in September this year. But the bank believes that
increasing fiscal pressure could force a reduction in capital
expenditure in a bid to rein in the deficit. This would aggravate
the infrastructural crisis, since capital expenditure has already
been cut from a level of 6 percent of gross domestic product at
the beginning of the decade to 3.4 percent at present, the ADB
said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB report has emphasized the need for the public sector to
play a key role in the development of the country's
infrastructure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
