<HEADLINE> NZ Announces New Traffic Rules to Cut Road Toll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Transport
Minister Jenny Shipley announced today a series of new tough
traffic rules in an effort to cut the country's road toll.
</P>
<P>
Among the new measures, police will have the power to
immediately suspend the license of a serious traffic offender and
can impound a vehicle driven by an unlicensed or disqualified
driver for 28 days.
</P>
<P>
They also include raising the minimum driving age from 15 to 16
and introducing a new style license with a photograph.
</P>
<P>
The new rules are designed to reduce the road toll and
particularly target drivers who speed or drink and drive.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said raising the licensing age balanced safety with the
needs of young people to drive for jobs, school or social
activities.
</P>
<P>
The measures came in line with the coalition agreement signed
last year, which promised to get tough with unsafe drivers, she
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
