<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Investment Falls This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
approved 569 foreign investment projects from January to September
this year worth 24.09 billion U.S. dollars, lower than that in the
same period last year, according to data revealed by the
Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM) today.
</P>
<P>
The number of approved foreign investment projects in the
January- September period of 1996 was 758 valued at 24.61 billion
dollars, the board said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the board also approved 546 domestic
investment projects with a total value of 91.36 trillion rupiah
(3,500 rupiah equal one U.S. dollar). In the same period last
year, domestic investment projects totaled 646 worth 82.53
trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The BKPM data also showed that most of the approved foreign
investment projects in 1996 were from Japan, which totaled 145
with a value of 7.56 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In second and third places respectively were Singapore, with
projects worth 3.1 billion dollars, and Thailand, with projects
worth 1.61 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Investment and BNPM Chairman Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo
said earlier he remained optimistic that the target of approved
foreign and domestic investment projects this year will match
that of last year, despite the ongoing monetary turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is hardly hit by the current monetary crisis in
Southeast Asian region. The Indonesian rupiah has dropped about 50
percent against the U.S. dollar this year. The government has cut
off many state budgeted projects worth 35 billion dollars in bid
to overcome the crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
