<HEADLINE> Thai Baht's Value Loses 48.3 Percent Since July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Thai currency has lost 48.3
percent of its value against the U.S. dollar in local trading
since the baht was floated three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The baht continued its slide Wednesday for the third day
running, hitting another record low of 39.90 offshore before
recovering to 38.55.
</P>
<P>
In local trading it closed at 38.25, losing 48.3 percent of its
value against the dollar since the baht was floated on July 2.
</P>
<P>
The further plunge of the baht was believed to have been
touched off by the country's political uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya announced his
resignation, which was followed by a mass cabinet resignation
announcement by leaders of the six coalition government parties
the same day.
</P>
<P>
However, the country will still have to wait for some time
before it sees the expected changes in the cabinet, in particular
the portfolios involving ministers in charge of economic affairs,
including a new finance minister.
</P>
<P>
While mass demonstrations have been held over the past three
days to demand Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's resignation
for economic failure, some labor leaders are staging a hunger
strike outside the home of Chatichai Choonhavan to urge his Chart
Pattana Party to quit the government.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Chatichai told labor leaders that their
call carried enough weight and he would call an urgent meeting of
senior party executives today to consider the request.
</P>
<P>
Chayawat Wibulswasdi, governor of the Bank of Thailand,
admitted Wednesday that the Thai currency's recovery depended on
positive political signs, adding "we hope to see a clearer
political picture and a speedy political solution."
</P>
<P>
"Politics is the only factor bringing the baht down. The
country has waited for too long for essential changes to be made
to the economic and political systems, and now we have to wait
longer," the Bangkok Post today quoted a Bangkok Bank trader as
saying, but did not give the trader's name. 
</P>
</TEXT>
