<HEADLINE> Senate Panel Reviews Clinton's Nominee For Civil Rights Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A Senate panel Wednesday
began reviewing U.S. President Bill Clinton's nomination of Bill
Lann Lee for the nation's top civil rights post.
</P>
<P>
If confirmed by the full Senate, Lee will become the first
Asian-American to hold the post of assistant attorney general for
civil rights in command of 250 lawyers.
</P>
<P>
During the testimony before the Senate Judiciary Committee
today, Lee called a California anti-affirmative action measure
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Affirmative action is a formal effort to provide increased
employment opportunities for women and ethnic minorities, to
overcome past patterns of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
A federal appeals court recently upheld the measure --
Proposition 209. An appeal is pending before the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
"This particular initiative violates the protection of the
14th Amendment," said Lee, who is a career civil rights lawyer and
Western regional counsel for the Legal Defense and Educational
Fund of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People (NAACP).
</P>
<P>
But Lee assured the senators that he is not the activist
ideologue that some critics say he is. He said the oath of office
would require him to enforce the laws as the courts decide them,
regardless of what he thinks.
</P>
<P>
Lee, a 48-year-old New York native and son of a Chinese
immigrant, began his career as an associate counsel for the NAACP
legal defense fund in New York in 1974. He moved to California and
the Center for Law in the Public Interest in 1983 before rejoining
the NAACP five years later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
