<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- German Dresdner Bank and China
Guotai Securities Co Ltd disclosed their intent to establish a
joint fund in the wake of a decision by China's central government
to choose several pilot firms to develop investment funds, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"The fund will be fully invested in domestic market for trading
A shares," said Zhao Dajian, deputy general manager of the Guotai
Securities Co, Ltd.
</P>
<P>
If licensed by the central bank, it would be the first
Sino-overseas fund allowed to invest in the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors are so far restricted to trading B shares
and overseas-floated shares of Chinese firms.
</P>
<P>
Allowing foreign institutions the access to A-share trading
would be a significant step in China's opening of the financial
market.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, China declared the long-awaited regulations
on investment funds would come soon and the country would choose
several pilot firms to develop funds.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said as China is increasingly integrated into the global
economic framework, it is inevitable that China's financial market
will open wider.
</P>
<P>
By learning the advanced techniques of foreign institutions,
China will be able to avoid steep fluctuations in the stock market
and promote the market's role in rational investment. 
</P>
