<HEADLINE> Volkswagen Leads China's List of Top 500 Joint Ventures (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Volkswagen Co.,
Ltd. has for the sixth consecutive year maintained its position as
the most successful overseas-funded industrial enterprise in
China, according to a report by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (Moftec) and the State Statistics Bureau
(SSB).
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen earned 24.3 billion yuan from sales in 1996,
followed by Motorola (China) Electronics, Ltd. and the Guangdong
Nuclear Power Corp.
</P>
<P>
Moftec and SSB listed the top 500 foreign-funded enterprises,
which includes the service industry for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Lu Jianhua, an official with the Foreign Investment Department
of Moftec, said that 124 overseas-funded enterprises had a sales
volume surpassing one billion yuan last year, up from 89 in
1995. The average sales volume rose by 205 million yuan to 940
million yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
She said that this year's top 500 chart shows that
overseas-funded enterprises in China are continuing to grow and
perform well.
</P>
<P>
The combined assets of the top 500 overseas-funded enterprises
stood at 491.5 billion yuan last year, 40 percent more than in
1995. Nearly 90 percent of the companies recorded a profit in
1996, with the total estimated at 36 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Their total sales volume rose to 469.8 billion yuan last year,
an increase of 27.8 percent over the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the structure of foreign investment has
further improved, with capital- and technology-intensive companies
claiming a bigger share.
</P>
<P>
"The top 500 are from 43 trades, with the majority converging
in electronics, machinery and food processing," Lu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volkswagen Leads China's List of Top 500 Joint Ventures (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The sales volume of the capital- and technology-intensive
companies accounted for 66.9 percent of the total last year, up
27.4 percent from the previous year, while the number of companies
in the textile and garment sector dropped to 45 from 53 in 1995,
and that for the food processing sector shrank from 37 to 32.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that for the first time less than half of the firms in
the top 500 are companies funded by the Hong Kong and Macao
regions, with European Union countries gaining a bigger share of
the China market last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of companies in the top 500 that were funded by Hong
Kong and Macao regions slipped from 257 in 1995 to 241 last year,
accounting for 48 percent of the total. Japanese companies
increased their presence from 66 in 1995 to 71, while American
companies showed a slight gain from 51 to 52.
</P>
<P>
Companies funded by Hong Kong and Macao on the list sold 212.2
billion yuan of products last year, at an average of 880 million
yuan each. The average figure was compared to 930 million yuan for
Japanese companies and 1.2 billion yuan for American companies.
</P>
<P>
"Although the EU countries' companies take up a comparatively
small share, they saw an apparent rise in sales volume," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume of the EU companies increased from 49.4
billion yuan in 1995 to 63 billion last year, up 27.5 percent,
with the average up from 1.3 billion yuan to 1.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
None of the overseas-funded companies from Qinghai, Tibet,
Xinjiang, Yunnan and Guizhou entered the top 500 chart, "but the
scale of the joint ventures in the central and western part of
China is on the rise," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume of the overseas-funded enterprises in the
central and western parts of the country reached 51.2 billion yuan,
or 10.9 percent of the total last year, topping the 25 percent
average growth rate in the coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
Some 88.8 percent of the overseas-funded companies on the list,
or 444, are from coastal regions, compared to 456 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong was home to the most successful overseas-funded
enterprises on the list, followed by Shanghai and Jiangsu.
</P>
</TEXT>
