<HEADLINE> FAO Warns Against Food Deficiency in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Food and Agriculture
Organization of the United Nations (FAO) warned here today that
Mongolia faces a serious food deficiency.
</P>
<P>
A special report released as the result of a fortnight-long
mission to Mongolia said the country's economic reform had led to
significantly more poverty, greater unemployment, lower
consumption, and cuts in social services and safety-net provisions.
</P>
<P>
The FAO report said 453,000 people, or about 20 percent of the
population, can now be described as poor. The most vulnerable
143,000, requiring urgent emergency, were identified as the
jobless, the elderly, female-headed households, children and
pensioners.
</P>
<P>
The number of poor people experiencing a dramatic fall in
nutritional standards was growing, the report said, and chronic
under-nutrition in children had risen to about 25 percent as poor
households shifted to cheaper and less nutritious foods.
</P>
<P>
"Without additional assistance, these groups, especially a
growing population of abandoned 'street children' will face great
hardship in the future," FAO said.
</P>
<P>
The organization estimated that food aid requirements for
1997-98 were 90,000 tons of which 23,000 tons should be emergency
food aid for the absolutely poor.
</P>
<P>
Mongolian agriculture has suffered heavily in the transition
from a centrally planned economy to a market one, and by the
withdrawal of substantial technical and economic assistance from
the former Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
