<HEADLINE> No Forbidden Zone for Foreign Funds, Says Bulgarian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan
Kostov stated that no forbidden zones exist in Bulgaria's economic
domain, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said foreign investors are also invited and welcome to
invest in shares of state-owned banks and insurance firms.
</P>
<P>
The country will advance its privatization campaign through
international investment intermediaries, the Bulgarian prime
minister said during a round-table conference on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The conference was sponsored by the London-based Economist
magazine. More than 140 Western economists participated.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Bulgarian government approved a list of 66
enterprises scheduled to be privatized through the use of foreign
funds, which is part of the country's 1998 privatization program.
</P>
<P>
Currently, non-state economies account for 18 percent of the
gross domestic product in Bulgaria. The government plans to make
the figure reach 49 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
The statistics released by the Foreign Investment Agency
indicate the country has received 2.1 billion U.S. dollars in
investment. During the first nine months of this year, some 413
million dollars poured into Bulgaria. 
</P>
