<HEADLINE> Business Co-operation, New Economic Growth in South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded businesses have
become a new force for economic growth in south China's island
province of Hainan and have contributed two-thirds of local fixed
assets investment.
</P>
<P>
The province has more than 5,000 foreign-backed enterprises,
with 11 billion US dollars of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded companies had 1.5 billion yuan in industrial
output value in 1996, accounting for 23 percent of the island's
total, and 48 million US dollars in profits from exports.
</P>
<P>
Hainan is also co-operating with domestic investors to set up
10,000 companies locally, at a cost of 22 billion yuan. And seven
of 10 local leaders in industrial output value and half of the 10
export leaders are involved in overseas or domestic investment.
</P>
<P>
A local foreign-funded company, the Hainan Asia-Pacific
Brewery, has had more than 14 million yuan in output value in one
month this year.
</P>
<P>
A 50-million-yuan pharmaceutical company, funded by Chinese
investors, generated 140 million yuan in output value during the
first half of the year, a 63 percent rise from the same period in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
