<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Banking System Stable: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines, in a fresh bid to ease concerns over the stability of
local banks, has reiterated that the country's banking system
remains stable and healthy due to its earlier measures to
strengthen it.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the status of local banks are better than
those in neighboring countries since they have lower exposure to
the real-estate sector and higher capitalization position,
according to today's local newspaper Today.
</P>
<P>
While other countries in the region have an average
commercial-bank exposure to the real-estate sector of 12.6
percent, including trust loans ending in the first quarter of the
year, the average exposure of local commercial banks stood at a
low 3.4 percent, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also said foreign-currency-deposit-unit (FCDU)
loans by local commercial banks were under control at 1.1 billion
U.S. dollars as of the end of this March.
</P>
<P>
It added that all borrowers of these FCDU loans are
structurally hedged against the risk of the current foreign
exchange rate afflicting the whole region.
</P>
<P>
The bank further supported its claim of a healthy banking
system by saying that local commercial banks' capitalization is
among the highest in the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the central bank, the relatively healthy position
of the banking sector, in part, is a reflection of the earlier
measures adopted by the monetary authorities.
</P>
<P>
These measures include a higher minimum capitalization
requirement, a 20-percent cap on real-estate lending and a
30-percent liquidity cover on FCDU liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Due to the weakening peso and the country's overheating
real-estate sector, several sectors, including the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), have expressed concern over the state of the
Philippines' banking community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Plans High-speed Upgrade of Railway Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Facing strong competition from
the rapidly growing air and motorway sectors, China's railway
industry is set to sharpen its edge by upgrading its existing
facilities while introducing a high-speed transportation network,
Today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"A feasibility study on the Beijing-Shanghai high-speed
railroad has been completed and submitted to the State Planning
Commission for further consideration," said Zhou Yimin, director
of the Science and Technology Department under the Ministry of
Railways.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement on Tuesday at a press conference for
the Modern Railways International Exhibition to be held at the
Shanghai Exhibition Center from June 2 to 6 in 1998. Its theme has
been defined as "raising the speed of passenger and freight trains
on existing lines and enhancing the capability of China in
developing technology and equipment for high-speed trains and
railways."
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is expected to showcase the latest technology
and updated equipment from approximately 200 manufacturers around
the world.
</P>
<P>
"We are now working around the clock on the preliminary study
for the 1,300-kilometre high-speed railway, and we have been in
discussions with companies from Japan, Germany, France, Spain and
Italy on the possible construction plan," Zhou said. "If the
project is approved, the first phase is likely to be built between
Shanghai and Nanjing in view of the economic strengthen of the
region and the short distance between the cities."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Railways is expected to pour 10
billion yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) into the establishment of
an advanced communications system on its current trunk lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
