<HEADLINE> Panamana Claim of U.S. Vigilance "Plant" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A Panamanian journal is
accusing the United States of installing a vigilance body under
the guise of the Anti-Drugs Multilateral Center (ADMC).
</P>
<P>
The daily "El Siglo", in today's editorial, said the U.S. was
setting about installing a hidden "watchful eye and a strong fist
of a policeman in Panama".
</P>
<P>
The newspaper wrote about the political and military
importance of the so-called enclave of the United States shortly
after the new round of talks between representatives of the two
countries began over the establishment of the ADMC.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the ADMC will work for the interchange of
information and intelligence data and facilitate military
operations in the region. It would be under the disguise of
fighting drug-trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Raul Leis, sociologist and columnist of daily "El Panama
America", said it is difficult to accept the claim that the ADMC
is a neutral institution and dedicated only to anti-drugs.
</P>
<P>
"The United States has repeatedly spoken of the foremost
geopolitical and strategic importance of keeping its military
presence in Panama, where it owns a solid infrastructure", said
Leis.
</P>
<P>
While one of the missions of ADMC was tackling drug-smuggling,
it also had the objective to ensure U.S. world hegemony and
national security, but in no way the interests and security of
Panama, the columnist said.
</P>
<P>
The 1977 Panama Canal Treaties require U.S. to withdraw its
troops from Panama no later than December 31, 1999 and return the
full administration of the Canal to the Panamanian government.
</P>
<P>
The accords were signed by Omar Torrijos and former
U.S. President James Carter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0298 </DOCNO>
