<HEADLINE> Videos on Breast Cancer Approved for Public Viewing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Operators of a local cable
TV station in the San Francisco area received approval today to
air two videos that were previously deemed "inappropriate" for
family viewing.
</P>
<P>
The Contra Costa County Board of Supervisors voted 5-0 to
permit the televising of the videos that teach women how to detect
breast cancer. The supervisors also approved a measure to fund a
longer TV program on breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
More than 185,000 women in the United States suffer from breast
cancer; the disease has a much higher incident rate in the US than in
Europe or Asia. The San Francisco area on the west coast is among
regions with the highest rates of the disease.
</P>
<P>
"We decided to make lemonade out of lemons," said one of the
county supervisors, hoping the controversy would help focus
attention on breast cancer prevention efforts.
</P>
<P>
Patricia Burker, the TV station's executive director, decided
not to televise one of the videos in question because it contained
five to six minutes of frontal nudity. She said it was more
appropriate for private viewing or in a doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
The program's producers as well as officials for the American
Cancer Society expressed outrage that a video intended to
save women's lives was yanked for being too racy.
</P>
<P>
At the board's meeting, several breast cancer survivors said
the educational programs should be aired to help educate
women who may not able to spot the early signs of breast cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnapping Cases Surge in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A total of 98 kidnapping cases
were reported to the authorities during the first nine months this
year in the Philippines, more than double the 47 cases registered
for the whole of 1996, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report from the Philippine National Police (PNP), the
Philippine Star said that kidnap-for-ransom gangs have raked in at
least 136 million pesos (4.5 million U.S. dollars) in ransom since
January this year.
</P>
<P>
The gangs have actually demanded a total of 435 million pesos
(14.5 million dollars) but the figure was lowered due to
negotiations between the victims' relatives and the kidnappers,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
But during the same period last year, only 34.9 million pesos
(1.2 million dollars) were collected by the kidnapping syndicates.
</P>
<P>
The PNP Criminal Investigation Group attributed the rise in
kidnappings to the growth in the number of kidnapping groups.
</P>
<P>
CIG director Chief Superintendent Efren Fernandez was quoted as
explaining that factionalim often prompted the breakup of some
bigger and better organized syndicates.
</P>
<P>
According to Fernandez, these lesser kidnapping groups are
giving the PNP a headache since they have started targeting small
and medium-scale entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the police report, a private anti-crime watchdog
group gave more alarming statistics on kidnap-for-ransom
incidents.
</P>
<P>
The well-known Citizens Action Against Crime (CAAC) was quoted
as saying Wednesday by Philippine Daily Inquirer that a total of
116 kidnapping cases occurred in the country during the first 10
months this year.
</P>
<P>
After paying a staggering 248 million pesos (8.3 million
dollars) in ransom, 184 victims, most of them Chinese-Filipinos,
gained freedom during the period, said the CAAC, a network of 75
non-governmental anti-crime organizations.
</P>
<P>
The group said three victims are still in the hands of their
abductors for failing to pay huge ransoms.
</P>
<P>
The group warned that the number of kidnapping incidents will
rise with the advent of the Christmas season, when kidnappers are
expected to intensify activities.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper reports said the official figures are
understandably smaller because many victims choose not to report
to the police in the wake of suspicions that many lawmen are
involved in kidnapping cases.
</P>
<P>
Kidnap gangs have been running rampant in the Philippines
during recent years, forcing many wealthy businessmen to live in
seclusion or just flee the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9,000 People Evacuated Due to Floods in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, October 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 9,000 people
were evacuated today from along the Parana and Uruguay rivers due
to floods caused by heavy rains, the Maritime Prefecture of
Argentina reported.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture said some riverside towns are in a critical
situation and many houses are in danger of being washed away by
flood waters along stretches of the two rivers.
</P>
<P>
Waters of the Uruguay River reached 13.90 meters high early
this morning, five meters above their normal level of nine
meters. They are predicted to reach 14.30 meters by midday with a
flow of 30,000 cubic meters per second, five times as much as the
normal average.
</P>
<P>
The Parana River had risen to a depth of 5.20 meters this
morning. People living in zones where there is danger of the
river overflowing were being evacuated.
</P>
<P>
There have been heavy rainfalls and hail storms in the
provinces in the past few weeks. Weather authorities say the
abnormal rains are caused by the El Nino phenomenon, which affects
South America every three or eight years; this time it's influence
is being felt throughout the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
