<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian dollar was sold down to its lowest level
against the greenback in two and half years yesterday as the
five-month-long Asian currency crisis deepened further. The local
dollar slumped overnight Tuesday, falling from 72.81 U.S. cents
to a low of 70.95 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Treasurer Peter Costello yesterday declared Australia a
haven from the economic turmoil in Southeast Asia, despite the
Australian dollar plunging to a two-and-half-year low after a
leading United states investment bank warned of harsh local
fallout.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard today was planning to use a
meeting with his British counterpart Tony Blair to try to avert
the Commonwealth heads of government meeting taking a tough line
on the greenhouse issue.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australia yesterday recorded its best inflation performance
for 35 years as fears about Southeast Asian crisis spilled over
into the local currency market, driving the dollar down almost two
U.S. cents to a 28-month low.  
</P>
