<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yabloko May Drop No-Confidence to Government: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Yabloko faction
would drop its no-confidence motion against the government if it
went through the problem of the taxation code to the end, leader
of the Yabloko parliamentary faction Grigory Yavlinsky said today.
</P>
<P>
Yavlinsky told reporters that the document which his faction
considered to be "senseless and harmful" should be recalled.
</P>
<P>
He meanwhile voiced the strong doubt that Sergei Baburin
representing the People's Power bloc in parliament would collect
the necessary number of signatures to initiate a no-confidence
motion against the government.
</P>
<P>
The Yabloko leader noted that once the head of the government
had recalled the taxation code from the Duma, "the issue of no
confidence would have died without any concessions to communists."
</P>
<P>
If the premier of the government did not withdraw the tax code,
he added, the code's handling under the Duma's procedure would
only result in "protracting this issue."
</P>
<P>
Another report said that Igor Shabdurasulov, a government
senior spokesman, today criticized the manner of Yavlinsky as
"unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
He told Itar-Tass in an interview that only an investigator had
the right to demand only a concrete `yes' or `no' answer to a
question, and not the leader of the Duma faction who was trying to
teach the chairman of the government how to fulfill orders of the
president.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin Tuesday sent a message to Duma
faction leaders, which contained an instruction to the government
to withdraw a draft tax code from the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Communist faction, the largest in the lower house
of parliament, today withdrew its motion of no-confidence in the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Concept Yields Wondrous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The operation of "one country,
two systems" between China and Hong Kong has yielded some wondrous
prospects after China's resumption of Hong Kong's sovereignty on
July 1, said Sir Peter Cazalet, president of China Britain Trade
Group.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar here today, Cazalet said, "I do not wish
to dwell on the past but to look at the future. As the title of
this seminar suggests, it is the future that interests us all the
most."
</P>
<P>
The seminar dealt in detail with issues relating to the
historic event, including Hong Kong's financial autonomy after the
handover, its role as a springboard into China and the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Cazalet stressed the enormous combined economic potential of a
China reintegrated with Hong Kong by quoting a research by Boeing
as saying that "over the next decade, China and Hong Kong between
them will buy 1,900 commercial aircraft at a cost of about 124
billion US dollars."
</P>
<P>
Not only will this make China the world's largest market for
commercial aircraft, but "I am right in saying that orders on this
scale are unprecedented anywhere, any time," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the 15th Congress of the Chinese Communist Party,
Cazalet said it is the most significant event to have happened in
China this year.
</P>
<P>
The reason is that the pronouncements by Chinese leaders "have
put beyond any doubt whatsoever China's intended path to become an
increasingly open, market-driven economy," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-British relations in future, Cazalet said, "The prime
minister, the foreign secretary and the president of the Board of
Trade are all due to visit China in 1998."
</P>
<P>
"This sends exactly the right signal to China about the
importance the UK attaches to its relationship with China," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
