<HEADLINE> Two US Air Force Aircraft Collide in Midair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- An Air Force T-38 Talon jet
trainer crashed today after an in-flight collision with an F-16
Fighting Falcon fighter jet at Edwards Air Base in southern
California, the Air Force announced.
</P>
<P>
The T-38 crashed shortly after the midair collision at Edwards
Air Force Base at 10 a.m. local time (1700 GMT) and the F-16 has
reportedly landed, but there is no immediately report on the
status of the crews, said an Air Force statement released at the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
The T-38 is a two-seater training jet, and the F-16 is a
single-seat jet.
</P>
<P>
The incident came just weeks after Secretary of Defense William
Cohen ordered all the services to perform safety "stand-downs" and
review their training procedures after a rash of air crashes.
</P>
<P>
On September 13, an Air Force C-141 transport crashed off the
coast of Africa. The next day, an F-117A Stealth fighter broke up
in flight at an air show in Maryland. The day after that a Navy
F-18 went down in Oman, and a Marine Corps F-18 crashed off North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, two planes from the New Jersey Air National Guard
collided off the New Jersey coast. 
</P>
