<HEADLINE> SAP Profits Soar by 86 Percent in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading software company
SAP AG today reported its pre-tax profits soared by 86 percent to
251 million marks (140 million U.S. dollars) in the third quarter
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The German company is expecting continued good performance in
the fourth quarter and the pre-tax profits for the year to hit a
record of about 1.5 billion marks (837 million dollars), up 50
percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The good news today sent SAP shares up 4.3 percent to close at
526 marks (293 dollars).
</P>
<P>
SAP attributed the explosive growth to the current strong
demand for standard software products R/2 and R/3 and the
continuing strength of the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months, data showed that the company gained
833 million marks (465 million dollars) in pre-tax profits, up
almost one-third over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The result was achieved on turnover of 3.8 billion marks (2.12
billion dollars), up 61 percent from the same period last year.
The figure was compared with a total of 3.7 billion marks 2.06
billion dollars) for all of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The German information technology firm said it expected that it
could get a listing on the United States stock market in the third
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
SAP, specializing in software used for running businesses, has
registered remarkable growth over recent years. It is Europe's
biggest and most profitable software makers and the only
non-American player among the world's top five software companies.
</P>
<P>
The company, based in rural Walldorf, will have 12,800
employees at the end of this year, compared with 9,200 at the end
of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
