<HEADLINE> IDB Finances Tax Modernization in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) today announced the approval of a 2.7
million U.S. dollar loan to Peru to help improve its tax system.
</P>
<P>
The resources will be used to assist the Nation Tax
Administration Service in the development of an integrated audit
system, the establishment of an electronic tax payment system, and
information systems enhancements.
</P>
<P>
The program, the third phase of IDB-backed modernization of
Peru's tax system, is designed to apply a realistic tax level to
contributors based on wealth and incorporate new taxpayers who
have the ability to pay but are not now paying.
</P>
<P>
The IDB financed the tax reform effort in Peru with 5 million
dollars in 1991 and, in 1994, 2.2 million dollars from the
Japanese Fund, which is administered by the IDB. Apart from the
IDB loan, local counterpart will contribute a total of 2.16
million dollars. 
</P>
