<HEADLINE> U.S. Tries to Hold Peace Talks between Afghan Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
intended to use a de facto cease-fire among warring factions in
Afghanistan to step up efforts for a negotiated peace, a senior
U.S. official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Karl Inderfurth, assistant secretary of state for South Asian
Affairs, told a Senate foreign relations subcommittee that U.S.
officials had talked with Russia, China and four other nations
bordering Afghanistan to determine ways to progress toward an
accord. And Britain and Japan will also be involved, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe that any side can win a military victory,"
Inderfurth said. "In our view all sides must recognize the
futility of fighting."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States is neutral in the Afghanistan
conflict but wants a multiparty government to emerge from any
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
While Inderfurth mentioned a "faint hope" for peace, another
witness, Zalmay Khalilzad, an analyst with the Rand Corp., said
prospects are not good. Part of the problem, he said, is the
Taliban, bent on a military victory, will not make a realistic
assessment of its recent setbacks and the resulting stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Taliban, which controls three-quarters of
Afghanistan, lost a key northern town to an opposition coalition.
</P>
