<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Presents his 1998-1999 Budget Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 2.583 billion dollars proposed budget for 1998 and 1999,
the Secretary-General's first since assuming office this year, is
20.3 million dollars less than that of the current two-year
period. The amount reflects a resource reduction of 124 million
dollars, as well as a 104 million dollars adjustment for
inflation and exchange rates prevailing in December 1996. For
the next two years, the UN chief initially proposed a staffing
level of 8,839, a reduction of 1,182 posts, including the
abolition of 904 posts.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said the initial proposal was
formulated according to the priorities set for the Organization
last year when the General Assembly adopted the medium-term plan
for the period from 1998-2001.
</P>
<P>
The total United Nations budget consists of the regular
budget and the extrabudgetary resources. But it is on the basis
of the regular budget that states' contribution are determined.
Each state is charged at a proportionate share of the budget
based on the scale of assessment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
