<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Unveils Global Warming Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today unveiled his proposals to curb the global warming,
suggesting gradual, mandatory reductions in greenhouse gases in a
longer time than the Europeans and environmentalists suggested.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's plan calls on U.S. industries to begin a path toward
reducing carbon emissions as soon as possible to bring them to
1990 levels over the next dozen years.
</P>
<P>
The proposal falls short of what the Europeans have demanded
and what many environmentalists have said is needed to address the
warming threat.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists as well as the Europeans have urged more
aggressive controls, including emission reductions of 15 percent
below 1990 level beginning on a limited basis as early as 2005.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said four years ago that the United States through
voluntary efforts could cap carbon emissions at 1990 levels by the
end of the decade, but emissions have been growing and are now
expected to exceed 1990 levels by 13 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry said today, "It would
be unrealistic to attempt to reach -- by the year 2000 -- 1990
levels on emissions... because it would most likely wreck the
world economy if you attempted to do that."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's basic theme is that global warming concerns can be
addressed through technology innovations and without new energy
taxes.
</P>
<P>
His proposal, which will serve as the U.S. position at
negotiations in Kyoto, Japan, in December, calls for industrial
nations to stabilize emissions at 1990 levels in the 2008-2012
time period and over the following five years make further
reductions.
</P>
<P>
It also would create a 5 billion U.S. dollars package of tax
breaks to spur energy efficiency and development of new energy
technologies that would allow a gradual shift away from fossil
fuels.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it would provide credits for industries that make
early emission reductions; develop an emissions trading program
among U.S. companies and among industrial nations to reduce costs
of carbon reductions.
</P>
<P>
The proposal calls for an agreement among industrial nations to
stabilize greenhouse gases over five years beginning in 2008
followed by unspecified reductions between 2012 and 2017.
Countries would be able to average annual emissions within the
five-year periods, allowing them to postpone reductions in some
cases.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also urged developing countries to make some commitment
on the matter before a treaty would be ratified and put into
effect.
</P>
<P>
"The United States will not adopt binding obligations without
developing-country participation," the White House said.
</P>
<P>
But developing countries suggest the industrial countries to
take the initiatives to curb the greenhouse gases as they are the
major gas creators. The United States alone currently accounts
for a quarter of all greenhouse gases going into the atmosphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shelton: U.S. Shares Little of NATO Expansion Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States share of
costs involved in expanding NATO would have little impact on the
nation's military spending, U.S. military chief told Congress
today.
</P>
<P>
"These costs are less than one tenth of one percent of the
Department of Defense budget," said General Henry H. Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
"What we gain from that, in terms of the NATO collective
security, I think, fully justifies that type of an expenditure,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic have been invited to
become full NATO members by 1999 and other Eastern European
nations, including Slovenia and Romania, also want to join the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate is scheduled to ratify the expansion treaty
next spring. But some Senators expressed concern that the costs to
American taxpayers could be greater than predicted by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon estimates that the total cost would be 27 billion
to 35 billion U.S. dollars. The three candidate nations would bear
much of the cost, with the rest shared by NATO members. The U.S.
share is put at about 200 million dollars over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The costs are to be determined at a NATO meeting in Brussels in
mid-December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
