<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford to Make Engines in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Ford Motor Company and Yuejin
Motors Group Corp. (YMGC) of China today announced an agreement to
form a 150,000 units per year engine manufacturing joint venture
in Nanjin, China.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony was held here today between visiting YMGC
president and general manager Huang Xiaoping and Ford vice
president and Ford China Operations president Vaughn A.
Koshkarian.
</P>
<P>
The 50/50 joint venture will make multivalve engines in the
range of 1.8 to 2.3 liters that will initially be used in the
various models of vehicles currently manufactured by YMGC, one of
China's pioneer vehicle manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
With total investment at 250 million U.S. dollars, the joint
venture will also form a technical development center for engine
localization and development.
</P>
<P>
Based in Nanjin, capital of Jiangsu Province, YMGC is presently
the largest light-duty manufacturer in China.
</P>
<P>
Ford officials said their company, U.S.' second largest car
manufacturer, has its history in China to be dating back to 1913
when it began selling Model T cars.
</P>
<P>
Ford's cooperation with the Chinese auto industry has
developed significantly over the past several years with five
other component ventures established, according to Ford's
officials.
</P>
<P>
They said Ford attaches importance to training Chinese
personnel with more than 300 Chinese engineers having received
training by Ford.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture "is clear evidence of Ford's commitment to
the Chinese people for the long term," said William Clay Ford, Jr.
chairman of Ford's Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
"We at Ford, are also hopeful of the continued strengthening of
the ties between the U.S. and China which we encourage this
through our people-to-people activities and our company-to-company
ventures," said Vaughn Koshkarian.
</P>
<P>
"We hope today's events set the tone for a productive visit for
President Jiang Zemin as he travels our country," he added.
</P>
<P>
Present at the ceremony were also leader of the Chinese
Economic and Trade Delegation Zeng Peiyan, State Planning
Commission Executive Vice Chairman, and Sun Zhenyu, Deputy
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is touring the U.S. mainly to purchase U.S.
goods prior to Chinese President Jiang Zemin's state visit to the
U.S. from October 26-November 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0356 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Offers Vast Business Opportunities: Zeng Peiyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States
are greatly benefited from the continuous expansion of their
economic and trade cooperation, said Zeng Peiyan, Executive Vice
Chairman of Chinese State Planning Commission here tonight.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, head of the Chinese Economic and Trade Delegation which
is visiting the U.S., expressed this at a special program arranged
by the National Committee on U.S.-China Relations.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech on "Seizing Opportunities and Initiating a
New Future", Zeng said the labor-intensive products exported to
the U.S. have created many jobs in China, as well as brought great
benefits to American retailers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he said, the technology-intensive products
imported from the U.S. such airplanes, machinery, electronics and
telecommunication equipment, have created tens of thousands of
direct job opportunities and millions of indirect job
opportunities, as well as help raise the technical standards of
China's industries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has so far invested in 23,200 projects in China with a
total investment of 15.7 billion U.S. dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dwelling on U.S. companies that have entered the Chinese
market, Zeng said the 1.5 billion dollar joint auto project
between General Motor and a Shanghai company started operation in
July and marked a new stage of U.S. direct investment in China.
</P>
<P>
With the phased opening of service industry in China, Zeng said,
the U.S. has become an active participant in this area.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, five U.S. banks have opened nine branches in China,
with one of them ratified to conduct domestic currency operation.
</P>
<P>
American International Group (AIG) has become the first among
the 6 foreign insurance companies approved to do business in China,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"Today, I am very glad to announce here that the Chinese
government has authorized AETNA Insurance Company to initiate
life insurance service in Shanghai," he declared.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. can obtain sizable profit by exporting to China
advanced technologies in the fields of environmental protection,
peaceful use of unclear energy, automobile and energy.
</P>
<P>
China urgently needs modern communications service, advanced
transportation network, fully developed wholesale and retail
industry, said Zeng, adding that the liberalization of such
service industries in China will provide broad business
opportunities for the U.S. which has a fully-fledged tertiary
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0357 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
