<HEADLINE> Meeting on Greenhouse Gas Emissions Opens in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The last preparatory meeting for
the global climate change conference in Kyoto in December opened
here today, with hope still remote for a breakthrough in setting
greenhouse gas emission limits for industrial countries.
</P>
<P>
Conference chairman Raul Estrada-Oyula from Argentina said more
could have been expected from Washington. The United States, along
with Japan, has been blamed for the failure to reach an accord on
how to reduce greenhouse emissions, which is linked to global
warming.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. commitment to reducing emissions was crucial to
reaching any agreement on the issue. The world's largest economy,
with only five percent of the world's population, produced 25
percent of the world's greenhouse emissions.
</P>
<P>
Washington has been opposing the European Union proposal for a
15 percent reduction in emissions from 1990 levels by the year
2010 and instead urging mandatory targets for developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the issue later today, U.S. President Bill
Clinton left out the call for mandatory targets for developing
countries, but his proposal for U.S. emission reduction fell short
of Europeans' goal.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. would try to reduce emissions to 1990
levels between 2009 and 2012, with further reductions over the
following five-year period.
</P>
<P>
U.S. emissions are currently 8.3 percent higher than 1990
levels.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also noted that the U.S. would not accept binding
limitations unless the developing countries participated
meaningfully.
</P>
<P>
His announced plan will be pursued by U.S. negotiators at the
Kyoto ministerial meeting on climate change.
</P>
<P>
As host of the Kyoto summit, Japan has suggested that a five
percent decline from the 1990 levels as a base for reducing
emissions, with individual countries being allowed to set their
own targets.
</P>
<P>
The proposal has met criticism from Europeans who said it was
too weak.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 officials from all over the world are attending
the current meeting in Bonn, which will last 10 days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
