<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Requests Domestic Abusers to Drop Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department
issued an interim policy today to request the military servicemen
to turn in their weapons to comply with a law prohibiting gun
ownership by people convicted of domestic abuse.
</P>
<P>
All the military's 1.4 million men and women are being required
to fill out a form to determine whether they had been convicted of
such an offense.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon expects the people affected would be in the
hundreds as most of the service members are young, unmarried and
unlikely to bring such a conviction with them, said Frank Rush,
the principal deputy assistant secretary for force management
policy,
</P>
<P>
Rush said there would be no exemption for people who are in
potential combat zones, such as Bosnia, but that he did not expect
the new policy to "adversely impact military readiness."
</P>
<P>
The discharge will affect anyone convicted after September 30,
1996, the date that the law was passed. If the conviction was
before that date, their guns will be taken away. But those people
will be allowed to appeal the older convictions or even apply for
a pardon, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Civilians who carry firearms, such as criminal investigators or
Pentagon police who work for the military, also come under the
law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
