<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0366 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Sign Letters for Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The China Huaneng Group, a
leading power development company of the country, signed
agreements here today with two major U.S. companies for
facilitating the Dezhou Power Plant of eastern China's Shandong
Province.
</P>
<P>
This is one of a number of signings brought by a high-level
Chinese trade delegation prior to the official U.S. visit of the
Chinese President Jiang Zemin. Sources said they have in their
hands a potential purchasing list worth more than 4 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two signings this afternoon involved two memorandum of
understanding to negotiate the contract for the design and
construction of a major expansion project of the power station,
which is planning to install a twin 660 megawatt (MW) generators.
</P>
<P>
The first one was signed with the Foster Wheeler Corporation,
the New Jersey-based leading U.S. company, which is intended to
provide highly technical boilers for the Chinese plant.
</P>
<P>
The other was signed between the Chinese company and the power
systems section of the General Electric Company, the major
manufacturer of power generators in the world.
</P>
<P>
Both of these two American companies were selected by the
Chinese after a series of bidding efforts, according to officials
of the project.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Peiyan, Executive Vice Chairman of the State Planning
Commission, who headed the Chinese delegation, said these two
American companies have set deep roots in China and now have also
set up good examples for other American investors.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Chinese delegation came with a very
serious intention to narrow the trade gap between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped that the two American companies would take a
long-term point of view and offer more competitive terms in their
further discussions with the Chinese partners.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, with the help of the China National Technical
Import and Export Corporation, are expected to sign their final
contracts in Beijing later this year.
</P>
<P>
Del Williamson, President of the Global Sales, GE's Power
Systems, said that the signing represents a significant milestone
in its supplying of power equipment and services in China.
</P>
<P>
Henri Bartoli, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Foster
Wheeler Energy International, Inc., said China is now its largest
market. They will be committed in providing their best technology,
equipment and services on the market.
</P>
<P>
Foster Wheeler Energy International, Inc. began its large-scale
investment in China in late 1980s. It has won reputation for its
technology of enabling it boilers emit no pollutants. Its combined
investment in China has topped one billion U.S. dollars. One of
its noticeable project in China was the Yangcheng Power Station in
Shanxi Province signed in August, 1996, for which it will provide
power for six 350 MW generators. The project is expected to be
completed in 2005.
</P>
<P>
GE traces its investment in China back to 1917, when it
installed two steam turbines in Yangshupu Power Plant in Shanghai.
Now there will be 56 GE steam turbines and 78 GE-technology gas
turbines installed or on order for power plants in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Argentina's Biodiversity Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of a 10.1 million U.S. dollar grant from
its Global Environment Facility (GEF) Trust Fund to help finance a
project which is to promote the conservation of biodiversity in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The project will establish five new national parks in poorly
represented ec-systems of recognized global biodiversity
importance.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide the support required to establish
the country's first biodiversity information network, creating a
fundamental tool required to assess the existing biodiversity
threats.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the World Bank resources, the Argentine government
will also fund some 11 million dollars for the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
