<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Confirms Control of Juba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese Armed Forces has
confirmed that Juba, an important southern town, is under the
control of government troops, the Sudanese news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the agency, General Mohamed Sounssi Ahmed,
deputy Chief of Staff in charge of security and intelligence, and
spokesman of the Sudanese armed forces, denied western media
reports that areas surrounding Juba are in the hands of Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA) led by John Garang, the largest
rebel faction in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
There were allegations recently from the SPLA that it had
controlled the river-course on the White Nile to Juba, but the
military spokesman said that the alleged rebel control of the
river-course was mere fabrications.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed confirmed the arrival of tugboats in Juba Tuesday, saying
that the tugboats, carrying supplies and foodstuffs from the
government to its troops in Juba, had not encountered any
resistance at Costi, the main port along the White Nile which is
the only course to Southern Sudan up to Juba.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also refuted allegations by the rebel movement
that it had controlled Eastern Equatoria State and inflicting
heavy losses upon government troops in the town of Toreet.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's civil war has claimed lives of over one million since
1983 when the southern rebels took up arms for greater autonomy
from the Islamic north for the Christian and Animist
south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
