<HEADLINE> U.S. Tries to Hold Peace Talks between Afghan Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
intended to use a de facto cease-fire among warring factions in
Afghanistan to step up efforts for a negotiated peace, a senior
U.S. official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Karl Inderfurth, assistant secretary of state for South Asian
Affairs, told a Senate foreign relations subcommittee that U.S.
officials had talked with Russia, China and four other nations
bordering Afghanistan to determine ways to progress toward an
accord. And Britain and Japan will also be involved, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe that any side can win a military victory,"
Inderfurth said. "In our view all sides must recognize the
futility of fighting."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States is neutral in the Afghanistan
conflict but wants a multiparty government to emerge from any
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
While Inderfurth mentioned a "faint hope" for peace, another
witness, Zalmay Khalilzad, an analyst with the Rand Corp., said
prospects are not good. Part of the problem, he said, is the
Taliban, bent on a military victory, will not make a realistic
assessment of its recent setbacks and the resulting stalemate.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Taliban, which controls three-quarters of
Afghanistan, lost a key northern town to an opposition coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0370 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat to Visit Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat will start visit Europe next Thursday
to meet European leaders on the latest development in the Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
His European tour starts in France and includes Germany, the
PNA-run Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The PNA and Arab countries have called for an active European
role in the peace process to balance U.S. mediation efforts which
have been accused of being in favor of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, which were suspended due
to Israel's settlement plans in Arab's East Jerusalem in March,
were resumed earlier this month after the mediation by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The JMCC also reported that the PNA reviewed the recent
development in the Palestinian-Israeli talks in its weekly cabinet
meeting this evening in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Arafat briefed the cabinet about the outcome of his meeting
with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai last night.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour meeting was held at Arafat's guest house on the
Palestinian side of the Erez checkpoint Between Jerusalem and Gaza
for two hours and the two leaders agreed to resume cooperation on
all security matters between the PNA and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Presents his 1998-1999 Budget Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 2.583 billion dollars proposed budget for 1998 and 1999,
the Secretary-General's first since assuming office this year, is
20.3 million dollars less than that of the current two-year
period. The amount reflects a resource reduction of 124 million
dollars, as well as a 104 million dollars adjustment for
inflation and exchange rates prevailing in December 1996. For
the next two years, the UN chief initially proposed a staffing
level of 8,839, a reduction of 1,182 posts, including the
abolition of 904 posts.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said the initial proposal was
formulated according to the priorities set for the Organization
last year when the General Assembly adopted the medium-term plan
for the period from 1998-2001.
</P>
<P>
The total United Nations budget consists of the regular
budget and the extrabudgetary resources. But it is on the basis
of the regular budget that states' contribution are determined.
Each state is charged at a proportionate share of the budget
based on the scale of assessment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0372 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
