<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Repatriates 400,000 Illegal Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 400,000 illegal
foreign residents in Saudi Arabia took advantage of a three-month
amnesty ending October 17 to leave for their home countries
without punishment, a senior Saudi official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Director General of the Interior Ministry's passports
department, Asaad Abdel Karim Al-Freih was quoted by Kuwait
News Agency in Saudi capital city of Riyadh as saying that
during the period, "400,000 illegal residents were allowed to
leave the country voluntarily and without penalty."
</P>
<P>
He also said that all illegal residents who reported to the
authorities within the period but could not be able to leave
because of transport problems were exempted from penalties.
</P>
<P>
He also said that so far 166,755 people have been able to
readjust their residency conditions and changed sponsors.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners make up one-third of Saudi population of 18
million. No official figures of illegal residents are available
but independent sources put the numbers of illegal residents in
the kingdom at 500,000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Saudi newspapers said the illegal laborers mainly
fall into three categories including those who entered the
kingdom with a "free visa" and were later set free by their
sponsors after arrival, those who deserted their sponsors as well
as those who overstayed after their visiting or residence visa
expired.
</P>
<P>
The majority of illegal residents are pilgrims who visited the
kingdom for the Haj season and stayed on after the expiry of their
Haj visa.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi authorities announced in July a three-month period
allowing the illegal residents leave without penalties and warned
that those who did not leave the country voluntarily in the period
would face punishments of up to six months in jail and a maximum
fine of up to 100,000 Saudi riyals (26,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Saudi nationals who have given shelter to overstayers and
people who breach residence and labor laws also risk being
fined up to 50,000 riyals (13,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Saudi authorities launched a crackdown on illegal foreign
laborers at the end of the three-month amnesty period as reports
said patrols from the immigration department have raided about
2,000 workplaces throughout the kingdom in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
But Al-Freih said so far no illegal residents were arrested
because "they all knew that our campaign was serious and that it
was impossible to stay in the country in an illegal manner."
</P>
<P>
A statement by the Interior Ministry said Monday night that
"citizens and expatriates were positively responding to calls for
cooperation issued by the ministry."
</P>
<P>
The departure of large numbers of unlicensed workers would
help regulate the local employment and labor market and boost
the country's Saudization plans, Saudi economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971023.0377 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shelton: U.S. Shares Little of NATO Expansion Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The United States share of
costs involved in expanding NATO would have little impact on the
nation's military spending, U.S. military chief told Congress
today.
</P>
<P>
"These costs are less than one tenth of one percent of the
Department of Defense budget," said General Henry H. Shelton,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
"What we gain from that, in terms of the NATO collective
security, I think, fully justifies that type of an expenditure,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic have been invited to
become full NATO members by 1999 and other Eastern European
nations, including Slovenia and Romania, also want to join the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate is scheduled to ratify the expansion treaty
next spring. But some Senators expressed concern that the costs to
American taxpayers could be greater than predicted by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon estimates that the total cost would be 27 billion
to 35 billion U.S. dollars. The three candidate nations would bear
much of the cost, with the rest shared by NATO members. The U.S.
share is put at about 200 million dollars over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The costs are to be determined at a NATO meeting in Brussels in
mid-December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
